\pard\keep\keepn\s1\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\i0\f0\fs28 What Is \i Cthulhu Eternal?\i0\f1\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\i\fs22 Cthulhu Eternal\i0  is a tabletop roleplaying game which allows you to play out a broad range of investigative adventures in different eras of history, as tainted by the ravages of H.P. Lovecraft\rquote s Cthulhu Mythos. \par
The only assumptions made by the \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  rules are that:\par
\pard\fi-360\li765\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The game takes place in an era of our planet\rquote s past, present, or future where humanity is the prevailing \endash  although not necessarily only \endash  species actively shaping the world.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The world is haunted by secret and mysterious survivals of otherworldly or extra-dimensional forces of Lovecraft\rquote s mythos; clues to their existence are scattered through written accounts (if such exist) or folktales passed from generation-to-generation.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Players take on roles of everyday people from the era, without special pulp-like \ldblquote super-powers\rdblquote ; regardless of their frailty they pursue the truth about the Cthulhu Mythos and ultimately work to thwart its corrosive influence.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Player characters are physical human beings that can be hurt, fall unconscious, or die if subject to physical damage \endash  and conversely, they can be healed using whatever knowledge of \ldblquote first aid\rdblquote  exists in the historical era.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Player characters are conscious and intelligent beings whose sanity can be adversely affected by witnessing terrible things beyond normal human comprehension \endash  and conversely, they can have their mental state made better by whatever folk-remedies or medical science exists in the historical era.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb480\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang3081\b\f0\fs28 Welcome to \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  Medieval \par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang1033\b0\f1\fs22 Muddy streets, violence, few areas of learning, rampant disease. Worried monks pray when the sea wolves are spotted but are blind to the horrors lurking in their scriptorium. A brave and bold knight pledges his love to a lady and receives his favor but pays no intention to the strange script on the gold band. A group of traveling pilgrims sing the songs of their Lord and offer his blessings to all in need. When they stop at a way house, who has more to fear the pilgrims and their strange beliefs or the locals and their strange beliefs? The \i druhzniki\i0  know there\rquote s nothing to fear in the woods except for the old woman and her rituals. A doctor looks out over the corpse strewn village center and knows this is only the harbinger of worse.\par
The Medieval period is one not typically associated with investigative horror, especially cosmic horror.  One question that frequently occurs is, how can player characters investigate cosmic horrors when cosmic horror\rquote s core conceit is that mankind\rquote s belief in the rational world is slowly, irrevocably being proven false and the medieval period, pre-industrial as it is, doesn\rquote t have a rational world to be melted away like January\rquote s ice on the Thames, exposing a dark, smelly meaningless morass underneath? Honestly, if a dark horror from beyond space and time disproves quantum physics to a villein from Winchester, he\rquote s not going to care. \par
Well, cosmic horror is all about the truths behind a world view being obliterated. During the Medieval period, science, progress, and rational thought are not the dominate worldview. That\rquote s for later in history as industrialization and the later scientific cosmology takes hold. Instead, during the Medieval period, those cosmic horrors are slowly, inexorably nibbling away at the corners of religion, the natural world, and social stratification \endash  what were cornerstones to the medieval mind understanding its world.\par
It\rquote s also important to realize investigative horror is very possible in a medieval world. And the player characters don\rquote t even need to have a modern worldview like a certain crime-investigating monk. Investigation is all about looking for clues, separating the wheat from the chaff, and arriving at conclusions. Crimes were investigated all the time. That was the primary task of many officials. They just used different tools and approached the problems from different angles. In other words, Medieval people weren\rquote t too stupid to solve investigations. They were just ignorant of many of the modern techniques players are used to. Because they didn\rquote t exist yet.\par
The \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  \i Medieval SRD\i0  covers a timeline that spans from 500 CE to 1300 CE and focuses geographically and culturally on Europe. This is a large span of time and can be broken down into two roughly defined periods:\par
\pard\fi-720\li1080\sa160\sl252\slmult1\bullet\tab Early Medieval spans 500 CE to 1000 CE\par
\bullet\tab High Medieval spans 1000 CE to 1300 CE\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 That\rquote s 800 years of history to cover. This SRD will cover the subject in the broadest of strokes. Future supplements will delve into chronological or geographical specifics.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb480\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang3081\b\f0\fs28 Investigations in an Age Medieval\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang1033\b0\f1\fs22 Much of the fiction that introduced the Cthulhu Mythos relies on reading only diaries, family histories, and newspaper accounts. The games that grew to emulate the cosmic horror genre relied on that same vehicle, written clues, to try to create a mystery for players to solve through their characters.\par
In a game set in a time where most people are illiterate, how can those clues be generated? Prior to widespread literacy information was still spread and consumed. It just used different forms and Game Masters can use those methods to provide clues to the player characters.\par
\b Folklore:\b0  When people gather, they tell stories. Many of those stories have a grain of truth to them. Stories can take the place of many Mythos tomes, with the added benefit that the same story can shift and change over time and geography. Player characters can encounter tales that seem wildly divergent that can be traced back to the same horrific origins.\par
\b Observation:\b0  People notice the world around them and get used to its rhythms and expected patterns. When those are upended, even slightly, people become nervous. The Mythos causes these interruptions in the world and people can learn about the Mythos in this manner. A hunter knows a deer, inside and out, but when he dresses one and finds it\rquote s infested with a writhing mass of worms that has completely replaced its internal organs. \par
\b The Written Word:\b0  The written word existed during the Medieval age. The tomes and grimoires that many people associate with investigative horror gaming only appeared in any quantity in the final 150 years or so of the era. Instead, clues might be hidden in bulls, pipe rolls, charters, contracts, and chronicles. Given the low literacy rate, player characters will need to determine if finding someone to read the document is worth the risk \endash  and the cost.\par
\b Communication:\b0  A lot of investigation boils down to communication. In the Medieval age communication between communities takes longer. In a world with slower communication, it\rquote s much easier for the Mythos to grab footholds in communities and never let go. \par
But within communities, word spreads fast and memories are long. Talking to people, asking questions, and listening to conversations and gossip is an excellent way for player characters to learn the truth about what\rquote s going on. In the absence of writing, stories, fables, and other elements of the oral tradition are used to retain and pass down information. People, or frequently groups of people, with prodigious memories could be considered the libraries of their day.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\lang3081\b\f0\fs26 History or Fantasy\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang1033\b0\i\f1\fs22 Cthulhu Eternal\i0  \i Medieval\i0  can be run as a historical setting, a dark fantasy setting, or anywhere in between. There\rquote s a concern that adding Mythos monsters into a historical Medieval setting runs the risk of turning the game into a straight-up fantasy game featuring creatures with unpronounceable names. \par
That could be a valid concern, but Medieval people were no more powerful than modern day investigators. If a creature is unaffected by shotgun blasts, a sword is going to be even worse because the wielder needs to get that much closer to the creature to use it.\par
While it\rquote s very easy to throw monster after monster at the player characters and turn the game into a dungeon crawl or Mythos hoedown, the Game Master can use the same tools they use in any era to ensure the game is investigative horror not hack-and-slash fantasy.\par
Rather than add Mythos monsters to create a fantasy world, Cthulhu Eternal Medieval aims to use those Mythos entities to create a legend haunted world. It\rquote s not likely that deep ones will take to the battlefield, but they might visit an otherwise unremarkable hamlet, one with long ties to the sea and numerous eligible partners.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 The Spiritual Being\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The Medieval Era in Europe was a spiritual one. The church dominated society and politics, often ruthlessly enforcing their views on those deemed unbelievers or heretics. The church\rquote s power waxed and waned throughout the period covered by this book, but religion always played a role in peoples\rquote  lives. It was the filter through which they interacted with the world. \par
Those who didn\rquote t want to run afoul of the powers that be toed the line unless they felt they had enough temporal power to stand up to church. And were usually brutally beaten down.\par
Those who deal with investigations into unnatural events or even scientific matters, are wise to couch their actions and findings with at least a nod to church. A healer knows which tincture will cure the infection, but always cautions the patient to pray.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 The Medieval Mind\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\b0\f1\fs22 Another question is how can a game where one of the core mechanics is the slow erosion of mental stability brought on by investigating the unnatural accurately portray a society that doesn\rquote t have a modern psychological view point?\par
While it\rquote s true that the people of the Middle Ages didn\rquote t have terms for post-traumatic stress disorder, depression, or psychopathy, the illnesses existed. What the Medieval people did understand was that trauma affects the mind and soul as much as it does the body, and people can suffer from afflictions of the mind and soul that show no physical wounds. The illnesses were there, the names for those illnesses were not.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 What Lies Ahead?\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Throughout this system reference document, rules will be provided to allow Game Masters to run investigative horror in the Medieval Age. No detailed setting is provided, but one isn\rquote t necessary to start playing the game.\par
\par
\pard\keep\keepn\pagebb\s1\sb480\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\b\f0\fs28 PART I: RULES OF THE GAME\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 This section describes the rules that all players will need to know to play a game of \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 . It describes:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How to \b create characters\b0  whose roles players will adopt in the shared Lovecraftian stories;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How characters make use of their \b skills and attributes\b0  to try to overcome challenges they encounter;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How \b combat\b0  works, when things turn violent;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How the fragile \b sanity\b0  of each player\rquote s character may become eroded by encounters with horrors, both mundane and unnatural;\par
\pard\fi-357\li714\sa120\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 What player characters can do during the quiet \b downtime\b0  between perilous adventures against unnatural entities.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-431\li431\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 1.0\tab Core Game Concepts\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 These rules tell you everything you need to know in order to play \i Cthulhu Eternal\f3 .\par
\i0\f1 As with most tabletop roleplaying games, when playing \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  one player takes on the responsibility of setting the scene and narrating the events which make up a \i Cthulhu Eternal \i0 adventure. That individual is termed the \b Game Moderator\b0 . All other players take on the roles of individual every-day people from an era of human history who are swept up in investigating the Cthulhu Mythos. These characters are called \b Protagonists\b0  (with the term capitalized for clarity). Protagonists will encounter a multitude of other characters whose roles are \i not\i0  being played by other players \endash  those characters are called \b Non-Player Characters\b0  (or NPCs) and their actions are controlled by the Game Moderator.\par
In this book you\rquote ll find rules for creating Protagonists and a full set of rules for running adventures in a Lovecraftian world of your group\rquote s choosing or devising.\par
In addition to this book, you also need pencils to record changes to your character sheet, scratch paper to draw sketches and take notes, and dice.\par
\i Cthulhu Eternal\f3  \i0\f1 uses polyhedral dice common to tabletop role-playing games: four-sided, six-sided, eight-sided, ten-sided, twelve-sided, and twenty-sided. The game plays best when you have a few of each on the table. Or you can find automated dice rollers on the Web and as mobile apps.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 1.1\tab Rolling the Dice\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 When the rules need you to roll dice, they use a particular nomenclature to save time and space: \ldblquote #D#,\rdblquote  as in \ldblquote 1D8\rdblquote  or \ldblquote 4D6.\rdblquote  The first number is the number of dice. The \ldblquote D\rdblquote  stands for \ldblquote dice with the following number of sides.\rdblquote  The second number is the number of faces on the die. \ldblquote 1D8\rdblquote  means roll one eight-sided die. \ldblquote 4D6\rdblquote  means roll four six-sided dice and add the numbers together. Sometimes you add or subtract a number from the roll. If it says \ldblquote 1D6+2,\rdblquote  that means roll one six-sided die and add two to the result.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 1.2\tab Percentile Dice (\ldblquote 1D100\rdblquote )\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Actions in \i Cthulhu Eternal\f3  \i0\f1 are resolved using \b percentile dice.\b0  That means you roll two ten-sided dice to get a number from 1 to 100. To do this, you don\rquote t add the individual die values together but instead treat each number as a digit (0\emdash 9). Before you make the roll, designate one die as the tens digit and the other as the ones digit. A zero (0) on the tens die counts as zero except when the ones die is also 0; then the 0 on the tens die counts as 10. For example:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The tens die comes up \ldblquote 0\rdblquote  and the ones die comes up \ldblquote 3\rdblquote : 03, or 3.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The tens die comes up \ldblquote 3\rdblquote  and the ones die comes up \ldblquote 0\rdblquote : 30.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Both dice come up \ldblquote 0\rdblquote : 100.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The tens die comes up \ldblquote 6\rdblquote  and the ones die comes up \ldblquote 2\rdblquote : 62.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 2.0\tab Protagonists\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Your Protagonist represents the fictional persona that you will control in the game. You will spend a lot of time navigating your Protagonist through exciting and dangerous situations, so it is worth investing time in creating a character you will enjoy playing.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 2.1\tab What Makes a Protagonist\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 All Protagonists are composed of six elements:\par
\b STATISTICS (STATS):\b0  Core capabilities for every Protagonist.\par
\b DERIVED ATTRIBUTES:\b0  Ratings that indicate physical and mental resilience, derived from stats.\par
\b ARCHETYPE:\b0  The type of role your Protagonist performs, which informs how many skill points and Bonds he or she has.\par
\b SKILLS:\b0  What training and education your Protagonist has picked up from being taught, or from life in general.\par
\b RESOURCES:\b0  An abstract rating that reflects your Protagonist\rquote s access to useful equipment or items.\par
\b BONDS:\b0  The people and communities your Protagonist fights to protect.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 2.2\tab Protagonist Creation\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Follow these steps to create a new Protagonist, or see \b HOW TO CREATE A PROTAGONIST\b0  on page \lang3081 8\lang1033  for a quick reference.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.1\tab STEP 0: Establish Harshness of Protagonist\rquote s Upbringing\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Most Medieval Protagonist\rquote s upbringings will have been tough, although a few may have had an easier childhood and others might have grown up in nightmarish circumstances.  Between you and the Game Moderator, decide whether the upbringing you envisage is best characterized by the descriptor \b Normal(-ish)\b0 , \b Harsh\b0 , or \b Very Harsh\b0 . The default for Medieval settings is Harsh, as described on page \lang3081 10\lang1033 .\par
Usually, an upbringing warranting the descriptor \b Harsh\b0  will involve the Protagonist having spent at least 3-4 years of adolescence in a highly dangerous or adverse situation that only affected the specific region. This calamity is likely to have caused the untimely death of at least a couple of the character\rquote s immediate family.\par
For an upbringing to be considered \b Very Harsh\b0 , the whole of the Protagonists childhood and adolescence was likely marred by a dangerous, deadly, or otherwise toxic environment that was particular to their region. This terrible situation is likely to have resulted in the majority of the characters\rquote  family suffering greatly, with at least half having perished.\par
Any upbringing that isn\rquote t \b Harsh\b0  or \b Very Harsh\b0  is considered \b Normal(-ish).\b0\par
A harsher upbringing might make him or her a little stronger or hardier (since only the strong and hardy would have survived), but at the cost of mental scarring from the many horrific sights marring their childhood. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.2\tab STEP 1: Determine Statistics\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Statistics are Strength (STR), Dexterity (DEX), Constitution (CON), Intelligence (INT), Power (POW), and Charisma (CHA). They range from 3 (the worst) to 18 (the best), with an average of 10 for an ordinary adult. Statistics represent core capabilities possessed by all Protagonists. All are important. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: STATISTICS\b0  on page \lang3081 9\lang1033 .)\par
You can create stats in two ways: rolling them or assigning points. Pick a method.\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b 1.\tab ROLL STATS: \b0 For each stat roll 4D6, drop the lowest of the four dice, and add up the other three. Place the six rolls in whichever stats you like.\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\b 2.\tab ASSIGN STATS: \b0 Divide 72 points among the six stats however you like, or pick one of the sets from page \lang3081 10\lang1033  and assign each score to one statistic.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 After the basic values are assigned for each statistic, modify according to the Harshness Descriptor for the setting:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 For Protagonists in \b Harsh\b0  settings: add 1 to \i either\i0  STR \i or\i0  CON (player\rquote s choice)\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 For Protagonists in \b Very Harsh\b0  settings: add 1 to \i both\i0  STR \i and\i0  CON\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.3\tab STEP 2: Calculate Derived Attributes\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Hit Points, Willpower Points, Sanity Points, and Breaking Point are derived from stats. They represent physical and mental resilience. When your Protagonist is hurt, exercises mental fortitude, or is traumatized, those scores can drop. If your Protagonist has a STR score that is outside the average range (9\emdash 12) he or she also has a modifier to the damage inflicted from hand-to-hand combat. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: DERIVED ATTRIBUTES & DAMAGE BONUS\b0  on page \lang3081 11\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.4\tab STEP 3: Select Archetype\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 What does your Protagonist do for a living (or just to stay alive)? Archetype dictates what skills your Protagonist has, his or her basic resource level, and the number of Bonds he or she possesses. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: ARCHETYPES\b0  on page \lang3081 12\lang1033 .) \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.5\tab STEP 4: Calculate Resources Rating\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 The Resources rating is a number between 0 and 20 that reflects the Protagonist\rquote s access to valuable or useful equipment. A Protagonist\rquote s base Resources rating is dictated by his or her Archetype, however during later steps, you can sacrifice other potential bonus skills in favor of a higher resources score; conversely, you can agree to drop Resources rating of 0 (entirely without access to resources) and receive additional skills. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: RESOURCES\b0  on page \lang3081 22\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.6\tab STEP 5: Define Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Bonds indicate the strength of relationships with the most important people and communities in your Protagonist\rquote s life \emdash  like a spouse, child, a long-time travelling companion, or a local community of people. Bonds help Protagonists resist mental trauma\emdash but as your Protagonist\rquote s life falls apart under the stress of the Mythos-haunted world, Bonds deteriorate. \par
There are \b two types of Bonds\b0  \endash  bonds with individuals and bonds with an entire community. The latter reflect the Protagonist\rquote s standing as part of the community and his or her ability to influence the group. \par
Each Individual Bond has a value that starts equal to your Protagonist\rquote s Charisma (CHA). \par
\pard Each Community Bond has a default value equal to half the Protagonist\rquote s Resources rating, however during creation of the Protagonist the player may elect to sacrifice potential skills in favor of a higher value. Conversely, the player may elect to take a Community Bond with a value of 1 (lowest possible social standing) and receive additional skills. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: BONDS\b0  on page \lang3081 26\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.7\tab STEP 6: Select Bonus & Adversity Skills\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Skills require special training, and come from schooling, experience, or personal interest. Skills are measured from 0% (no training) to 99% (foremost expert in the world). (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: SKILLS\b0  on page \lang3081 31\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.8\tab STEP 7: Determine Mental Damage from Harsh Environments\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Protagonists that have grown up in difficult and brutal conditions are likely to have picked up some mental scarring along the way. This can leave them hardened to certain types of traumatic stimuli, distant from those around them, or afflicted with mental disorders. (see \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: MENTAL DAMAGE FROM HARSH UPBRINGING\b0 , page \lang3081 40\lang1033 .)\par
