\pard\intbl\cf0\b0\f1 In Medieval settings, most people live a wretched life. To reflect this, the default Harshness indicator for a Protagonist\rquote s upbringing is \b Harsh\b0 . That means that characters typically begin with a +1 boost to either STR or CON (the fact that they have made it to adulthood makes them among the healthier representatives of their communities) and some bonus skill picks; however any character whose CHA or POW is below 7 will have suffered some isolation as described in \b MENTAL DAMAGE FROM HARSH UPBRINGINGS\b0 , page \lang3081 40\lang1033 .\par
Protagonists who were born into privilege \endash  sons and daughters of nobility or similar \endash  may have avoided the squalor of everyday life. Such (rare) characters can be considered to come from a \b Normal(-ish)\b0  upbringing, gaining neither the bonus to STR/CON nor suffering the potential mental costs of a harsh upbringing.\par
While the \i default\i0  throughout the 800 years covered by this SRD is for Harsh environments, that is not to say that there weren\rquote t isolated times and places where life was even worse \endash  warranting a \b Very Harsh\b0  indicator. The Anarchy in England; the Great Famine across Europe; the Crusades across Europe and into the Mediterranean; the Black Death; the Magyar and Mongol invasions from the Steppes; Jewish massacres, expulsions, and rising antisemitism are all examples of times and places where the Game Master might want to rate a Protagonist\rquote s upbringing as Very Harsh. \cell\row\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang3081\par
