\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10348\pard\intbl\sb120\sa120\sl276\slmult1 In Medieval settings, not every adult can read and write. The limited (or non-existent) education opportunities available to most individuals means that only a relatively small percentage of people are literate. Such skills are usually limited to professions which routinely involving reading or writing documents. Being illiterate doesn\rquote t mean you can\rquote t communicate verbally \endash  but it does make it difficult or impossible to understand any information encountered in written form.\par
\pard\intbl In game terms, literacy is represented by the Protagonist\rquote s rating in the Literacy skill (described in the skill listings in Section 2.10.5). By default this skill begins at zero, although some archetypes furnish the Protagonist with a higher starting score. If you want your Protagonist to be able to read and write you should reserve some bonus skill picks to ensure a Literacy skill rating of 40% or more.\cell\row\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.5.2\tab List of Archetypes\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 The following Archetypes are appropriate for games of Lovecraftian investigation set in Medieval eras. Archetypes represent the roles that player characters fulfill in society. An archetype could represent the life a player character had before they were drawn into investigating cosmic horror. Or it could represent the role they still try to maintain to the best of their ability while the horrors slowly erode everything they thought they understood. \par
Each archetype has a collection of skills that represent knowledge areas the player character uses in their daily lives. \par
\pard This list doesn\rquote t cover every possible character type but focus on likely protagonists in mystery and investigation tales. The GM is encouraged to develop other archetypes to cover other character types suggested by players. Guidelines for developing new Archetypes may be found on page \lang3081 94\lang1033 .\par
