\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Members of the same gang or band (see \b BONDS FORMED THROUGH SHARED ADVERSITY\b0 , below)\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Spiritual counsellor\i\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\f0 Changes to Individual Bonds During Play\par
\pard\cf0\i0\f1 Bonds\rquote  scores often deteriorate because of your Protagonist\rquote s experiences of the horrors of the Mythos-haunted world. A Bond increases if it is cultivated between adventures (see \b DOWNTIME\b0  on page \lang3081 80\lang1033 ). An Individual Bond can never have a score higher than your Protagonist\rquote s CHA. Any time CHA drops, each Individual Bond drops by the same amount.\par
Individual Bonds are vulnerable. If the Protagonist learns that the individual has died or gone permanently insane, the Bond is destroyed. The Bond is also permanently broken when its score drops to 0 (see \b BROKEN BONDS\b0 , nearby).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.2\tab Community Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A Community Bond is a relationship between the Protagonist and a broader community of individuals; it reflects the Protagonist\rquote s status within that community, and the likelihood of other people following his or her instructions or desires. \par
A community may be a geographical association of people or it may be a society of like-minded individuals (e.g., a club, congregation, or association). A Protagonist can have more than one Community Bond, each describing his or her status within the hierarchy of a different societal structure.\par
Community Bonds are measured on a scale of 1 to 20, with an indicative meaning shown below:\par
\b Rating\tab\tab What the Rating Represents\par
\pard\b0 1\tab\tab Disgraced member; on the verge of being banished from the society.\par
2-4\tab\tab Shunned member of the community; someone who is actively looked down on by most\par
5-8\tab\tab Standard member of the community; one of the pack, whose opinion is unlikely to matter\par
9-12\tab\tab Well-regarded member of the community; favorably viewed by many other members\par
\pard\fi-1440\li1440 13-16\tab Important member of the community; respected by most other members\par
17-18\tab Influential member of community, involved in most decision-making; liked by most\par
19\tab An extremely influential member of the community, looked up to by virtually everyone\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 20\tab\tab Top-tier of leadership in the community; the head honcho.\par
\pard If a Community Bond is chosen during the creation of your Protagonist, it typically begins with a default rating of \ul half\ulnone  the Protagonist\rquote s Permanent Resources rating, rounded up (see \b RESOURCES\b0  on page \lang3081 22\lang1033 ). In a few cases, a Protagonist\rquote s Archetype indicates that he or she has a Community Bond with a certain fixed rating \endash  the final rating should be either that value or half the Permanent Resources rating, whichever is higher. \par
This value can be optionally increased during the creation of your Protagonist by sacrificing one or more \b BONUS SKILL POINT\b0  picks (see page \lang3081 30\lang1033 ); the first skill pick sacrificed in this manner gives a bonus of +5 to the Community Bond\rquote s rating; each subsequent sacrifice adds +2 (to a maximum of 20). \par
It is also possible to elect for your Protagonist to take a Community Bond with a rating of 1 (and suffer the social effects of being a pariah to fellow members) and receive one extra Bonus Skill Point Pick to use on purchasing skills later in the process.\par
\b Sample Community Bonds\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\b0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Group which shelters in the same place\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Church or support group\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Craft or trade guild\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Secret society\i\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\f0 Changes to Community Bonds During Play\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 The rating for a Community Bond applies individually to every member of that community, and to the community as a whole. If a Community Bond decreases in value, the relationship with each member of the community deteriorates. A Community Bond is permanently broken when its score drops to 0 (and the Protagonist is likely cast out of the nominated community). \par
If the community itself is entirely destroyed (e.g., every member killed or sent insane), or if the Protagonist permanently leaves it (e.g., by relocating to live in a new region) the bond is destroyed.\par
If a Community Bond is broken by either means, the Protagonist will likely suffer negative impacts (see \b BROKEN BONDS\b0 , nearby).\par
During play, events may arise where the reactions of NPCs from the Protagonist\rquote s bonded community (or the community as a whole) have an impact. In some cases, the Protagonist may instigate such situations (e.g., by requesting aid from the community or trying to convince them of impending danger). In such situations the Game Moderator may ask for a test against \b Community Bond Rating \'d7 5.\b0  Success means that the NPC or the community reacts favorably.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.3\tab Describing Bonds\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Identify each Individual and Community Bond: \ldblquote My Wife.\rdblquote  \ldblquote My Husband and Kids.\rdblquote  \ldblquote My church congregation.\rdblquote  \ldblquote The Society of Amateur Sleuths.\rdblquote  \par
An Individual Bond must be a real person or group of people who the Protagonist believes to be alive, and with which there is some (potential) opportunity to interact. \par
A Community Bond must be a real group who recognizes the Protagonist as a member.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.4\tab Broken Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 When a Bond deteriorates, that relationship becomes strained. Exactly what shape that takes in play is up to you and the Game Moderator (playing the NPCs). \par
Bonds often fall apart because of events beyond your Protagonist\rquote s control. An example for Individual Bonds: your Protagonist\rquote s husband might leave for another woman. An example for Community Bonds: a new leader might ascend to power who is actively antagonistic towards your Protagonist.\par
If such a disaster harms the subject of a Bond, that reduces the Bond\rquote s value by 1D4. If that disaster permanently removes the subject of the Bond, that Bond is gone. Cross it off the sheet.\par
\pard When damage to a Bond reduces it to 0, the relationship is damaged beyond repair. Cross it off the sheet. The only way to regain a Bond with that character or community is to build it from scratch as if it had never existed (see \b DOWNTIME\b0  on page \lang3081 80\lang1033  for details on creating new Bonds).\par
The breaking of any Bond is almost certainly traumatic and is likely to trigger a Sanity test due to Helplessness (see page \lang3081 70\lang1033 ).\par
When you cross a Bond off your Protagonist\rquote s character sheet, don\rquote t erase it. After all, there\rquote s no forgetting a vital relationship that went bad. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.5\tab Bonds Forged Through Shared Adversity\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Protagonists often band together into small tight-knit groups, to enhance their chances. This is true when the group is alone in the wasteland; it\rquote s often also true even when they are outsiders in a larger settlement. If those tight-knit groups go through terrifying ordeals together, there is a strong chance that they will become psychologically bound together through that shared experience. \par
\pard\sl276\slmult1 In game terms, groups of Protagonists tend to form individual bonds to one another when they spend most of their time fighting the forces of the Mythos. Whenever your Protagonist is part of a team that completes a harrowing adventure, there\rquote s a chance of such trauma-generated bonds forming or deepening. This is the case if the scenario played out in a way where:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 One or more members of the team suffered temporary insanity, or\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 One or more members of the team gained a new psychological disorder, or\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 One or more members of the team died or was incapacitated by physical injuries, or\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa120\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Any other event occurred that the Game Moderator thinks was shocking enough to constitute severe trauma.\par
\pard In the downtime after the adventure (see \b DOWNTIME\b0  on page \lang3081 80\lang1033 ), all Protagonists that made it back must make a SAN test. If the roll succeeds, nothing changes. If your Protagonist fails the SAN roll, he or she gains or strengthens an individual bond with EACH fellow Protagonist who also made it through the same trauma (up to a maximum of five fellow Protagonists). \par
\pard\sl276\slmult1 For each such fellow trauma-sufferer,\par
\pard\fi-360\li825\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If your Protagonist has \b no previous bond\b0  with that person, he or she gains a brand-new individual Bond to that person at a rating equal to half your Protagonist\rquote s CHA. Add the new Bond to your Protagonist\rquote s character sheet. This focusing of attention comes at a detrimental cost to other pre-existing Bonds \endash  you must lose 1D4 points from one other bond of your choice (either an Individual or Community Bond).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If your Protagonist \b already has an Individual Bond\b0  with that person, the bond is increased by 1D4 points (up to a maximum value equal to CHA); at the same time 1 point must be subtracted from another bond of the player\rquote s choice (either an Individual or Community Bond). Note that even if all your Protagonist\rquote s existing bonds are already at the maximum score (and hence can\rquote t increase), you still need to pick a bond to weaken by 1.\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1 Remember that if a Bond is ever reduced to 0 or less it is broken, as per the previous section. \par
When choosing a Bond to weaken during this process you CANNOT pick a bond to an individual who was with your Protagonist on the recently completed adventure. You MAY, however, pick an Individual Bond gained from an earlier shared traumatic encounter.\par
Rather than treating this as a mechanical process, you and your Game Moderator are encouraged to work together to describe the changed dynamic between your Protagonist and those around them. If points have been gained with fellow adventurers, does that mean they are beginning to feel comfort that their colleagues will always have their back? Or has the shared experience kindled a romance of sorts? Conversely, if a bond has been weakened, does that mean the Protagonist has been neglecting a member of their circle of friends and both are now feeling their friendship is slipping away? \par
If a community bond has weakened does it mean that the excessive time spent socializing with the tight-knit group has alienated others in the community to the point that they have lost confidence in the Protagonist? Or has he or she just missed so many gatherings that their standing as a high-status member of society has eroded?\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 2.9\tab Detailed Description: Bonus Skill Points\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The skill package associated with your Protagonist\rquote s Archetype coupled with the Adversity skills from the harshness of his or her upbringing, represent his or her core proficiencies. But they certainly aren\rquote t the full story about everything the Protagonist is good at. \par
Each Protagonist \b begins with ten Bonus Skill Point Picks\b0 . Each pick provides a boost of 20 points to whichever skill it is applied. Alternatively, some of these skill picks can be \b traded-in\b0  for non-skill benefits instead (see box nearby). \par
When applying a skill pick to a skill which has NOT been set by the Protagonist\rquote s Archetype or increased through Adversity Skill Picks, then add the 20 to its \b base rating\b0 . Otherwise, add 20 to its \b current score\b0 . This allows your Protagonist to specialize in certain Archetypal skills or to learn a little about skills not included in his or her Archetype. You can even boost a single skill more than once, adding +20 each time. \par
Unless the Game Moderator says otherwise, you can\rquote t raise a skill higher than 80% during Protagonist creation. You must assign (or trade-in) all bonus points to skills before play begins.\par
