\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb160\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 3.0\tab The Game\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\i\f1\fs22 Cthulhu Eternal \i0 is a game about unveiling \endash  and perhaps defeating \endash  the horrific yet hidden entities of the Cthulhu Mythos that haunt our reality. The world seems mundane, but this is a fa\'e7ade. In dark corners and hidden places, the extra-dimensional and extra-terrestrial horrors lurk. Most people never learn of their existence, but some come to worship or follow such inimical forces. Others who learn the true nature of reality \endash  of those dark entities, and insane devotees they inspire \endash  cannot help but make a stand to defeat their terrible plans. These are Protagonists. Their fight might be never-ending, but the cost of losing is too great. They are the line that separates the sane world we know and the Apocalypse.  \par
\lang3081 Protagonists are usually every-day people -- from any class of society -- who have been awakened to the truth about our world. They usually aren't superhuman, powerful, or invulnerable. Rather, they are frequently humble, vulnerable, and fragile individuals who have chosen to fight the unknowable but vast powers of the Cthulhu Mythos. Not because they have the strength to conquer the horrors, but because the consequence of inaction is beyond the pale.\lang1033\par
Here\rquote s how the game works.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 3.1\tab Using Skills\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The\i  Cthulhu Eternal \i0 rules focus on \i skills\i0 . You decide what your Protagonist attempts to do; the Game Moderator determines what skill to use. In a typical adventure, Protagonists use many different skills.\par
Sometimes using a skill requires a roll of dice. The most important rule is this: \i The Game Moderator determines if, when, and what you roll\i0 . If the Game Moderator says a roll isn\rquote t needed, the skill rating itself determines success or failure.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.1.1\tab Resolving a Test Without Dice\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 If the Game Moderator decides you don\rquote t need to roll, it comes down to what you\rquote re trying to do and how high your Protagonist\rquote s skill is. If the fact is common knowledge for your Protagonist\rquote s Archetype, or can be found with a little research, he or she might be able to get it by just expending time and effort. If it requires special knowledge, your Protagonist may need a certain amount of a skill.\par
If the Game Moderator thinks a fact should be known by a history expert with at least 60% skill, then a Protagonist with a relevant history-related skill at 60% or better knows the fact without rolling. Or perhaps a Protagonist with 40% can learn some clues but a Protagonist with 60% would learn more.\par
Sometimes a combination of skills can overcome a lack in one. A clue that needs 60% in a history-related skill might be available if the Protagonist has both a history skill \i and\i0  some other relevant skill at 40%.\par
\b How Much Skill Does the Task Require?\par
\pard\b0 Only a little training; a hobbyist \tab\tab\tab 20%\par
Basic training or minor training\tab  \tab\tab 30%\par
Years of experience or training\tab\tab\tab 40%\par
Decades of experience or training\tab\tab 60%\par
A lifetime\rquote s mastery \tab\tab\tab\tab 80%\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.1.2\tab Resolving a Test With Dice\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 If the Game Moderator tells you to roll a skill, it\rquote s a skill test. The dice determine success or failure. Roll two ten-sided dice to get a number from 01 to 00 (1 to 100).\par
Roll your skill test rating or lower to succeed. Rolling higher than the skill test rating means failure.\par
There are three criteria for rolling dice for a skill test:\par
\b ROLL WHEN IT IS DIFFICULT:\b0  A skill test means the Protagonist is attempting something \i difficult\i0 . After all, even an expert in a skill might have only a 60% or 70% rating. A skill test is for a situation when even an expert might fail.\par
\b ROLL WHEN THE SITUATION IS UNPREDICTABLE:\b0  Having to roll means the situation is out of control. Randomness plays a major role. Surprising, possibly disastrous things can happen, no matter how skillful you are.\par
\b ROLL WHEN THERE ARE CONSEQUENCES:\b0  Failing a skill roll means ugly things are going to happen. Maybe failing at the crisis is the punishment \emdash  or with a failed roll, your Protagonist succeeds but the consequences are severe. The fallout is up to the Game Moderator.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.1.3\tab If You Don\rquote t Have the Skill\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 If your Protagonist has a 0 in a skill, he or she can\rquote t even attempt to use it. It requires specialized training or education that your Protagonist lacks.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.1.4\tab Using a Stat\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 If your Protagonist tries to do something that anyone ought to be able to do \emdash  something that\rquote s hard, but doesn\rquote t require specific training like a skill \emdash  then the Game Moderator might look to one of your Protagonist\rquote s stats, for a stat test. A stat test is the relevant stat \'d7 5. (So with STR 11, a STR test is 55%.)\par
Use STR if the challenge requires physical power, CON if it requires endurance, DEX if it requires agility, INT if it requires attention to detail, POW if it requires mental resilience, or CHA if it requires charm.\par
\pard The stat\rquote s score itself may tell the Game Moderator whether your Protagonist succeeds, without the need for a roll. Does it need someone with at least average Strength? Then your Protagonist needs a STR of 10 or more. If it needs someone with above-average Intelligence, your Protagonist must have an INT of at least 13. If only one person in a hundred would have enough stamina, your Protagonist needs a CON of 17 or 18. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: STATISTICS\b0  on page \lang3081 9\lang1033 .)\par
\b How Much Stat Does the Task Require?\b0\f7\fs24\par
\f1\fs22 Anyone could do it \tab\tab\tab\tab 3\endash 4\par
Nearly anyone could do it \tab\tab\tab 5\endash 8\par
An average person could do it \tab\tab\tab 9\endash 12\par
Only an unusually gifted person could do it\tab 13\endash 16\par
Only a prodigy could do it \tab\tab\tab 17\endash 18\f7\fs24\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs22 3.1.5\tab Bonuses and Penalties\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Having to make a skill test in the first place means there\rquote s a substantial chance of failure. But if the odds are really against your Protagonist, the Game Moderator might impose a penalty, down to a minimum chance of 1%. If the situation is a little more in your Protagonist\rquote s favor, the Game Moderator might allow a bonus, up to a maximum chance of 99%.\par
If a bonus or penalty applies, it\rquote s usually +20%/\u8722?20% or rarely +40%/\u8722?40%.\par
