\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.1.6\tab Who Rolls?\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A group of Protagonists is searching the cult leader\rquote s camp. Who makes the Alertness skill roll to spot a trap? Good question.\par
If it\rquote s a task where having more help is useful, use the highest skill among the team.\par
If it\rquote s a task where a crowd is a hindrance, use the lowest skill among the team.\par
If it\rquote s a task where you need to know whether every Protagonist succeeds or fails (\ldblquote How many of you get a good look at the thing in the shadows?\rdblquote ), each player rolls.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 3.2\tab Success and Failure\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 On any skill or stat test, there are only four possible outcomes. From best to worst they are: \i Critical Success, Success, Failure, \i0 and \i Fumble\i0 . Ordinary success and failure are most common. Critical successes and fumbles represent exceptionally good or terrible outcomes.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.2.1\tab Critical Success\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A critical success is a roll of 01 or any success where the dice digits match one another. So if your Protagonist\rquote s skill is 50%, you achieve a critical success with a roll of 01, 11, 22, 33, or 44. A critical success automatically succeeds, and exceeds expectations. A critical is \i twice as good \i0 as an ordinary success. What twice as good means must be taken in context of the action. \b In combat, a critical success means double damage\b0 , but during an investigation, it might mean the action takes half as long.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.2.2\tab Success\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A success is a roll \i equal to or less \i0 than the test chance. With a success, your Protagonist accomplishes what he or she set out to achieve.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.2.3\tab Failure\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A failure is a roll that\rquote s \i higher \i0 than the test chance. Sometimes that means your Protagonist suffers harm.\par
There may be times when a failed roll means a Protagonist achieves what he or she wanted \emdash  but it comes with an unpleasant complication. The Game Moderator always decides whether that\rquote s the case and what the cost will be. For a few possibilities, see the effects of fumbling a roll.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.2.4\tab Fumble\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A fumble is a roll of 00 (100) or any failure where the dice digits match one another. So if your Protagonist\rquote s skill is 50%, you fumble on a roll of 55, 66, 77, 88, 99, or 00. A fumbled roll fails, no matter how high your Protagonist\rquote s chance of success, and has additional, catastrophic consequences.\par
\lang3081 In a horseback chase, a fumble might mean your Protagonist's mount stumbles or collides with an obstacle. When parrying a sword blow, the Protagonist's weapon might break, or their shield be permanently damaged (perhaps even becoming heavily worn or junk)\lang1033  \par
The exact complications are up to the Game Moderator. Here are some possibilities.\par
\b PHYSICAL STRAIN:\b0  Lose 1D6 HP \i or \i0 temporarily lose 1D4 STR, CON, or DEX.\par
\b EMOTIONAL BURNOUT:\b0  Lose 1D6 WP \i or \i0 temporarily lose 1D4 INT, POW, or CHA.\par
\b ALIENATION:\b0  Offend an important NPC. All CHA or \b Persuade\b0  tests with the NPC automatically fail until the end of the adventure.\par
\pard\b EXHAUSTION:\b0  Immediately become \b\caps exhausted\b0\caps0  (see page \lang3081 47\lang1033 ).\par
\b DISTRACTION:\b0  Suffer a \u8722?20% penalty to your next test.\par
\b CONFUSION:\b0  You make a major error and gain false information.\par
