\clcbpat7\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10797\pard\intbl\b >\lang3081 > Optional Rule: Nudging Skill and Stat Tests\cell\row\trowd\trgaph108\trleft5\trbrdrl\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrt\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrr\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw10 \trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10797\pard\intbl\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang1033\b0 By default, as soon as dice are rolled for a skill test or a stat test the result is set in stone \endash  the number rolled determines whether the test was a success, failure, critical success, or fumble. There is no way to change the roll or to re-roll to achieve a different outcome.\par
Some players, however, prefer to have an option for dice rolls to be nudged: for \ldblquote near misses\rdblquote  to be turned into successes at some other cost to the character. This optional rule delivers that, by allowing characters to sacrifice Willpower Points (WPs) to \ldblquote nudge\rdblquote  the dice rolled for a skill or stat test. Using this optional rule makes the game slightly less harsh in terms of the randomness of the dice, but also adds a resource-management element to players rationing their Willpower Points.\par
\pard\intbl\sl276\slmult1 Here\rquote s how nudging works for skill tests and stat tests:\par
\pard\intbl\fi-360\li720\f2\'b7\tab\f1 After a test has been rolled, a player can elect to spend any number of WPs, with each spend adjusting the dice roll either up or down as the player prefers.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Each WP spent adjusts the original dice roll by \b 1\emdash 5 percentiles (player\rquote s choice)\b0 .\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1\ldblquote Nudging\rdblquote  a dice roll that originally indicated a failure may convert it into a roll indicating standard success; alternatively, a dice roll that was originally a standard success may be turned into a failure.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 This process cannot be used to alter the dice roll for a test performed by someone other than the character making the WP spend. Specifically, it cannot be used to modify the dice roll of an adversary.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The sacrifice of WPs represents the character investing extra energy and focus to ensure that a borderline situation is resolved in the desired way. Doing this can trigger exhaustion and may make the tired character more susceptible to being affected by arcane powers, and less prepared to participate in rituals.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1\ldblquote Nudging\rdblquote  a dice roll can never create a critical success or a fumble, and dice rolls that originally indicated a critical success or fumble cannot be \ldblquote nudged\rdblquote . Even if the dice roll total obtained after a \ldblquote nudge\rdblquote  is applied happens to be a number with matching digits, the result is still either a standard success or a failure.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Remember that, as described in \b WILLPOWER POINTS\b0  (page \lang3081 46\lang1033 ), consequences may apply to a character whose WP total falls below 3. \par
\pard\intbl\sb200 Note: only skill tests and stat tests can be \ldblquote nudged\rdblquote  in this way; SAN test and Luck tests cannot be \ldblquote nudged\rdblquote . \cell\row\trowd\trgaph108\trleft5\trbrdrl\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrt\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrr\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw10 \trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clcbpat7\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10797\pard\intbl\i A\lang3081 s with all optional rules, the GM and players should agree before the game whether this rule is to be used. \par
Another question to agree upon is whether \ldblquote nudging\rdblquote  is available \ul solely\ulnone  to Protagonists in the game or also an action that NPCs can perform. \cell\row\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\lang1033\b\i0\f0\fs26 3.3\tab The Luck Roll\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Events often come down to pure chance. \par
\lang3081 Are adversaries awake when your Protagonist sneaks into the enemy\rquote s camp? Does the stolen reliquary have an ampoule of holy water? When water spills through a leak in the ship's hull and ignites its secret cargo of Greek Fire, are you standing next to it?\lang1033  \par
If the Game Moderator calls for a Luck roll, there\rquote s a 50% chance that things go your Protagonist\rquote s way. It doesn\rquote t depend on psychic talent or your Protagonist\rquote s connection with the cosmos or anything else. Just roll the dice. With a critical success or a fumble, your Protagonist\rquote s luck is extra good or bad.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 3.4\tab Time Required\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Sometimes speed counts. The Game Moderator determines how long it takes to perform a test.\par
\pard\b TURNS:\b0  It takes a few combat turns (see \b THE TURN \b0 on page \lang3081 48\lang1033 ) or, at most, sixty seconds. Combat, some skill tests, and most stat tests are resolved in turns.\par
\b MINUTES:\b0  It takes a few minutes. You can\rquote t do it in combat, but otherwise, your Protagonist can get through it rapidly. Many skill tests are resolved in minutes.\par
\b HOURS:\b0  It takes hours. Your Protagonist can typically attempt two to four such tasks per day (four only if your Protagonist goes without rest; see \b EXHAUSTION\b0  on page \lang3081 47\lang1033 ).\par
\b DAYS:\b0  It takes a day or more. Some extended skill tests, requiring multiple rolls, take days.\par
\b LONG-TERM:\b0  Efforts that take place outside normal gameplay, like research and training, fit here. It could be a week, a month, or years. It\rquote s up to the Game Moderator.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 3.5\tab Opposed Tests\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 An opposed test happens when someone takes action to interfere with another\rquote s action. \par
\lang3081 This might be a player rolling a Protagonist\rquote s Insight to sense the lies in a rich merchant\rquote s Persuade roll, a Protagonist escaping a pursuer with opposed Athletics tests, a degenerate cultist trying to wrestle a sacrificial victim to the ground in opposed Unarmed Combat tests, or a Protagonist\rquote s Dodge trying to oppose an alien monstrosity\rquote s attack roll.\lang1033\par
Usually, skills oppose skills and stats oppose stats. A stat opposes a skill only when one character must use very specific knowledge or training (and therefore rolls a skill) but the other does not (and therefore rolls a stat). It is up to the Game Moderator.\par
By nature, opposed tests are very unlikely to succeed. Not only must your roll succeed, but you must overcome the opposition\rquote s roll as well.\par
If two characters\rquote  skills oppose each other but neither needs to roll, the higher rating wins.\par
