\clcbpat8\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx1814\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx6067\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10687\pard\intbl You Succeed\cell A critical success beats a success. Otherwise, whoever rolled higher succeeds and the other fails.\cell Your action succeeds and the opposed action fails.\cell\row\trowd\trgaph108\trleft5\trrh269\trbrdrl\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrt\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrr\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw10 \trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clcbpat8\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx1814\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx6067\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10687\pard\intbl You Fail\cell You fail to stop the opposed action.\cell Nobody succeeds; or whoever rolled lower succeeds and the other fails (Game Moderator\rquote s choice).\cell\row\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 3.6\tab Pursuit\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 A pursuit is a series of opposed tests. The most basic chase is a single test for each side, pursuer and quarry. If the quarry wins, he or she escapes and the chase ends. If the pursuer wins, he or she (or it) runs the quarry down and the chase ends. Usually that means combat.\par
A more prolonged chase may require two wins by one side or the other. Wins cancel each other out. If the pursuer wins one but the quarry wins the next, that cancels out the pursuer\rquote s win. Then, the quarry needs to win twice more to escape. An especially wide-open chase might require three wins to either catch up or escape.\par
In each test, one side or the other wins. If both fail their rolls, the lowest failure wins. A critical success with a chase test counts as two wins. A fumble counts as two failures thanks to a wreck or some other disastrous accident.\par
\b WHICH SKILL APPLIES:\b0  \lang3081 A chase on foot requires Athletics; one in a wagon or cart uses Drive; one on a waterborne craft uses a Sailing specialization; in the water, it uses Swim; on horseback, it uses Ride.\lang1033\par
\b AID AND ADVANTAGES:\b0  Coordinating with multiple pursuers (whether they\rquote re in sight of each other or have constant contact by some means), or being substantially faster and/or more maneuverable grants a +20% bonus to each chase test, or +40% if the advantages are overwhelming.\par
\b SEEKING AN EDGE:\b0  Instead of the usual roll to catch up or get away, pursuer or quarry may attempt to gain some advantage by testing a skill that applies to the situation.\par
\lang3081 Possible skills include Alertness, Navigate, or Stealth.\lang1033  \par
If this test wins the contest, instead of a \ldblquote win\rdblquote  it grants a +20% bonus to the next chase roll, or +40% with a critical success. Failure and fumbling have the usual effects.\par
\pard\b COMBAT DURING A CHASE:\b0  A person in a chase may be able to launch attacks at opponents, especially if their skill isn\rquote t being used as the test for escaping or evading (e.g., they are a passenger on a conveyance controlled by someone else). These will usually be some form of ranged attack. Such attacks are resolved \i before\i0  the pursuer and quarry roll to pursue and escape. Attacks use the \b COMBAT\b0  rules, beginning on page \lang3081 47\lang1033 . Each contest in the chase is equivalent to one combat turn. \par
If your Protagonist makes an attack but doing so \i will\i0  seriously impact their efforts to pursue or evade, the attack is considered to occur instead of a roll to pursue or escape \endash  effectively meaning the opponent\rquote s roll to pursue or escape automatically wins that exchange. This will always be the case if the pursuit is on foot; in other situations it will depend on whether your Protagonist\rquote s skill at controlling his or her conveyance is a major factor in the chase (if in doubt, the GM can make a call).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 3.7\tab Willpower Points\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Willpower Points are mental fuel. Protagonists require Willpower Points to keep going despite exhaustion, to resist unwanted persuasion, to resist the effects of terror and mental disorders, and, on rare occasions, to resist or enact unnatural rituals.\par
\b LOW WILLPOWER POINTS:\b0  A Protagonist whose WP hits 1 or 2 has an emotional breakdown. The Protagonist suffers a \u8722?20% penalty to all actions until WP rises above 2.\par
\b RUNNING OUT OF WILLPOWER POINTS:\b0  A Protagonist at 0 WP loses all control. This can look different for every Protagonist and every situation. The Protagonist might collapse in wracking sobs, or lash out wildly, or simply pass out. The Game Moderator controls your Protagonist until WP returns to 1 or higher and describes the reaction. A Protagonist with 0 WP cannot succeed at \i any\i0  tests, including SAN tests. Sooner or later the Protagonist falls asleep, regardless of any disorders or stimulants, long enough to regain WP\par
\b REGAINING WILLPOWER POINTS:\b0  When your Protagonist gets a full night\rquote s sleep (but no more than once in a 24-hour period), he or she regains 1D6 WP. If you play up one of your Protagonist\rquote s personal motivations in a way the Game Moderator finds compelling, your Protagonist regains 1 WP.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.7.1\tab Exhaustion\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A Protagonist who works too long or faces extreme danger and injury without resting becomes exhausted. When this comes into play is up to the Game Moderator, but a good rule of thumb is that going a night without sleep or refusing to rest after losing SAN or Hit Points leads to exhaustion.\par
An exhausted Protagonist suffers a \u8722?20% penalty to all skills, stat tests, and SAN tests, and loses 1D6 WP. The exhausted Protagonist loses another 1D6 WP after going another night without sleep, after working hard for a few hours, or after running or fighting for a few minutes. A full night\rquote s sleep cures exhaustion.\par
\lang3081\b STIMULANTS:\b0  Taking common types of stimulants offsets the exhaustion penalty for 1D6 hours. Examples in the Medieval Age might include caffeine, gruit, and mushrooms.\par
During this time, your Protagonist can\rquote t sleep. A Protagonist can take more stimulants to keep going, but every dose after the first costs 1D6 WP.\par
\pard If your Protagonist gains a new mental disorder while using stimulants, the Game Moderator has good reason to say the disorder takes the form of addiction to them. \lang1033 (See \b DISORDERS\b0  on page \lang3081 73\lang1033 .)\lang3081\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang1033\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 3.7.2\tab Sleeplessness\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 The first time your Protagonist tries to sleep after suffering temporary insanity or gaining a new mental disorder (see \b TEMPORARY INSANITY\b0  and \b DISORDERS\b0  on page \lang3081 72\lang1033 ), you must make a SAN test. If it fails, your Protagonist wakes in terror, losing the possibility of regaining any WP for 24 hours.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b ARTIFICIAL SEDATION:\b0  A Protagonist may try to overcome sleeplessness via artificial means, such as drinking alcohol or using other similar sedatives. This gives a +20% bonus to the SAN test to get to sleep. If the test fails, the Protagonist gets no rest despite taking sedatives. In addition, the Protagonist is sick the next day, at a \u8722?20% penalty to all tests until he or she gets a full night\rquote s rest. If your Protagonist gains a new mental disorder while using sedatives, the Game Moderator has good reason to say the disorder takes the form of an addiction to them.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb480\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 4.0\tab Combat\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 A serious fight, where people are trying \cf3 to kill each other, is chaotic, frightening, and fast. That\rquote s what these rules represent. Being skilled, having better weapons, or being in a superior position helps, but the inescapable randomness of combat can claim even the most skilled combatant\rquote s life.\par
Lovecraft\rquote s fiction presaged humanity\rquote s urge to reduce any confrontation with the unnatural to base combat. However, humanity\rquote s weapons are as ridiculous to the unnatural forces that control the universe as an ant wielding a pebble is to the bulldozer razing the field the ant hill stands in. Combat rarely resolves any unnatural threat.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.1\tab The Turn\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Combat is measured in \i turns\i0 . A turn is a few seconds, or as long as it takes everyone to complete a single action.\par
The Game Moderator counts down by DEX for all characters, from highest to lowest. Each character acts when his or her number comes up. If DEX scores tie, the actions occur at the same time or the Game Moderator can choose some tiebreaker.\par
During a turn, a combatant can attempt \i one \i0 of the following actions.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.1\tab Aim\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Sacrifice one turn to aim and gain a +20% to your attack next turn. Aiming requires no roll. After the next turn, or if your Protagonist suffers any damage before attempting it, the bonus is lost.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.2\tab Attack\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An \ldblquote attack\rdblquote  encompasses anything from throwing a punch to \lang3081 firing a Trebuchet\lang1033 . The \ldblquote standard\rdblquote  attack (ranged or hand-to-hand) is a skill test to see if your Protagonist hits a target; damage is inflicted based on the weapon used. \par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang1024\f2\'b7\tab\lang3081\f1 Use \b Ranged Weapons\b0  for aimed weapons (e.g., bow or crossbow);\lang1033\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Use\b  Athletics\b0  for a thrown weapon;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Use \b Melee Weapons\b0  for a hand-to-hand weapon;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Use \b Unarmed Combat\b0  for a punch or kick.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang3081 The number of shots fired in a single ranged weapon attack may depend on the weapon used \emdash  e.g., a  skilled archer might fire two arrows at once from a longbow \emdash  but it\rquote s always a single attack roll and a single damage roll.\lang1033\par
\pard Attacking with unarmed combat or a melee weapon (but not with weapon which acts at a distance) also means your Protagonist is parrying and blocking. See \b DEFENSE ROLLS\b0  on page \lang3081 51\lang1033  for details.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.3\tab Called Shot\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A called shot is an attack to a particular body part (the head, the hand, the leg). \par
\lang3081 A called shot allows your Protagonist to fire an arrow through a narrow opening, or to shoot someone in the leg and avoid body armor.\lang1033\par
A called shot is more difficult than a standard attack, so it has a penalty:\par
\b PARTLY COVERED (\u8722?20%):\b0  The target is partially covered (half the body).\par
\b MOSTLY COVERED (\u8722?40%):\b0  The target is mostly covered (all but a limb or head).\par
\pard Making a called shot with unarmed combat or a melee weapon (but not with weapon which acts at a distance) also means your Protagonist is parrying and blocking. See \b DEFENSE ROLLS\b0  on page \lang3081 51\lang1033  for details.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.4\tab Disarm\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An attempt to knock an object from the target\rquote s grasp using the Unarmed Combat skill. This is possible only if your Protagonist has both hands free and is in hand-to-hand range. If your roll succeeds, the target drops the object.\par
\pard Attempting to disarm also means your Protagonist is parrying and blocking. See \b DEFENSE ROLLS\b0  on page \lang3081 51\lang1033  for details.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.5\tab Dodge\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 This is a \b Dodge\b0  skill test to get out of the way of an attack (or a disarm or pin). This opposed test pits your Protagonist\rquote s Dodge skill against the attack roll. If your roll overcomes the attack roll, your Protagonist avoids harm. See \b DEFENSE ROLLS\b0  on page \lang3081 51\lang1033  for details. If the Game Moderator agrees, a Protagonist can dodge while jogging or running as described in the \b MOVE\b0  action below.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.6\tab Escape\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 A roll to escape a pin. Roll either \b STR\'d75\b0  or \b Unarmed Combat\b0 , whichever is better. This acts as a defense roll against the character pinning your Protagonist (see \b DEFENSE ROLLS\b0  on page \lang3081 51\lang1033  for details); it\rquote s opposed by the pinning character\rquote s attack roll against your Protagonist. If the pinning character is not attacking, the escape is opposed by either \b Unarmed Combat\b0  or \b STR\'d75\b0  (whichever is better). If the escape roll succeeds, your Protagonist is no longer pinned \emdash  and the escape roll defends against other attacks until your Protagonist\rquote s next action. If it fails, your Protagonist remains pinned and cannot defend against attacks.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.7\tab Fight Back\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 If someone attacks your Protagonist with a melee weapon or unarmed combat (not a weapon acting at a distance or an explosive), your Protagonist can fight back with \b Unarmed Combat\b0  or \b Melee Weapons\b0  to block and counterattack. See \b DEFENSE ROLLS\b0  on page \lang3081 51\lang1033  for details.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.8\tab Move\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An action that moves your Protagonist a significant distance: 10 yards jogging, 20 yards running, or 30 yards sprinting (or you can move about 3 yards while performing some other action).\par
Usually moving requires no roll, but if Protagonists are running or sprinting, players may need to make a \b DEX\'d75\b0  test to keep their footing. Fail, and your Protagonist falls prone and must spend a turn recovering.\par
\pard If there\rquote s cover at the end of your Protagonist\rquote s movement, getting behind it provides protection (see \b PROTECTION IN COMBAT\b0  on page \lang3081 56\lang1033 ). This can give your Protagonist armor against ranged weapons and explosives \emdash  if the Protagonist is behind cover when the attack happens.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.9\tab Pin\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An attempt to immobilize a target, either on the ground or up against something, using \b Unarmed Combat\b0 . This is possible only if your Protagonist has both hands free and is in hand-to-hand range. If it succeeds, the target is pinned. \par
\i All \i0 unarmed or melee weapon attacks against a pinned target are at a +20% bonus. A Protagonist pinning a target can attack the pinned target in later turns.\par
A pinned target can attempt escape once per turn (see the \b ESCAPE\b0  action, above) but nothing else.\par
\pard Attempting to pin a target also means your Protagonist is parrying and blocking. See \b DEFENSE ROLLS\b0  on page \lang3081 51\lang1033  for details.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.10\tab Wait\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Protagonists can choose to wait to take any action after their DEX order comes up. At any time before your next turn, you can insert your Protagonist\rquote s action before the next action in DEX order. Your Protagonist can\rquote t wait until another character acts and then jump in before it\rquote s resolved, but your Protagonist can jump in before the other character\rquote s turn comes up.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.1.11\tab Anything Else\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Drink a vial full of a glowing liquid, throw open an unlocked door, activate a mechanism, grab a rope, pick something up, stand up from a prone position \emdash  anything that takes a moment\rquote s concentration. The Game Moderator decides whether it requires a stat or skill test.\par
