\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Dodging and hand-to-hand combat (with unarmed or with melee weapons) are tests that protect your Protagonist by opposing an attack roll.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.3.1\tab Dodging and Fighting Back\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Your Protagonist can Dodge or fight back against an incoming attack even before your Protagonist\rquote s DEX order in a turn. If you do this, it becomes your Protagonist\rquote s single action for that turn. A Protagonist who has already taken another action that turn can\rquote t Dodge or fight back until the next turn.\par
A roll to Dodge opposes \i all \i0 hand-to-hand attacks that turn. It lets your Protagonist duck behind cover to evade all ranged attacks that turn if cover is near. Dodging never inflicts damage.\par
\lang3081 Fighting back blocks not only the current hand-to-hand attack, but may also deflect (or parry) later hand-to-hand attacks in the same turn, albeit at some potential risk (see below).\lang1033  If you win the contest, you take no damage. It does not protect you against ranged attacks unless you\rquote re close enough to push the ranged weapon away. As part of your fighting back roll, choose one offensive action \endash  \b\caps attack, called shot, disarm,\b0\caps0  or \b\caps pin \b0\endash  \caps0 against a single attacker. If your roll beats that attacker\rquote s roll, your Protagonist takes no damage and your Protagonist\rquote s action affects the attacker.\par
In order to Dodge or fight back, your Protagonist must know an attack is coming and be physically able to block or evade it. If your Protagonist is pinned, if the attack occurs before he or she realizes it, or if your Protagonist can\rquote t see or hear the attacker, your Protagonist can\rquote t Dodge or fight back.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.3.2\tab Dodging Ranged Attacks\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An ordinary Dodge roll can avoid a slow-moving ranged attack, such as an arrow or a thrown weapon. \par
\lang3081 If your Protagonist is aware that such an attack is imminent, and they are standing close to an appropriate source of cover, make a Dodge roll for the Protagonist to scramble behind that cover before the attack. If there\rquote s no cover, Dodging does no good.\lang1033\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.3.3\tab Defending After Attacking\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 When your turn comes up, declare your Protagonist\rquote s action \caps\emdash\b  attack, called shot, disarm, or pin\b0\caps0  \emdash  and make the roll. Your Protagonist can harm, disarm or pin only one target per turn (the attack might hurt others, but all attacks have a single target).\par
A successful roll to attack, disarm, pin, or make a called shot can be re-used later in the same turn to oppose subsequent \b Unarmed Combat\b0  and \b Melee Weapons\b0  attacks against your Protagonist. This is called parrying, and carries a certain level of risk. When an attacker declares such an attack against your Protagonist \endash  but before any dice have been rolled \endash  you can elect to parry the attack. The alternative is to simply choose to allow the attack to continue unopposed. If you decide to parry, the attacker makes their skill test and it is compared in an opposed test against your Protagonist\rquote s dice roll from earlier in the turn (either a direct attack/pin/called-shot or a Fight Back). \par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If your Protagonist\rquote s result is superior to the new attacker\rquote s result, then the attack has been fully deflected and neutralized \endash  no harm is done to your Protagonist. \par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 However, if the attacker\rquote s roll achieved a better result in the opposed test, not only does your Protagonist take damage from the attack, but he or she \b also\b0  \b loses 1WP\b0 . This \lang3081 represents the cumulative mental toll of parrying \endash  tracking, predicting, and reacting to multiple opponents who want to do the character bodily harm.\lang1033\par
\pard If your Protagonist is carrying a shield at the time of the attack, the act of parrying (re-using a previous attack roll) is much less risky from a WP perspective. Each shield type has an associated number of \ldblquote free parry\rdblquote  actions (see the table on page \lang3081 57\lang1033 ). While utilizing such a defensive item, your Protagonist can parry up to the stated number of times in the turn \i without\i0  risking loss of a WP \endash  success in such parry attempts deflects harm, failure results in normal HP damage but no loss of WP. Considering the relatively small number of WPs most Protagonist\rquote s possess, the slow rate and which they refresh, and the possibility that extended melee combat may lead to an accumulation of significant parry-related exhaustion, shields represent a significant tactical advantage.\par
To parry an attack, your Protagonist must know the attack is coming. That requires seeing or hearing the attacker. The Protagonist must \i also \i0 be physically able to block the attack, if it is melee. A pinned Protagonist can\rquote t defend, nor can a Protagonist who has already successfully pinned a target.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 An attack roll with a ranged weapon does not oppose attack rolls against your Protagonist.\par
