\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10461\pard\intbl\sl276\slmult1 The Lethality rating replaces the need to roll lots of separate attacks and lots of dice for damage. Without it, a massively damaging attack might require several separate attacks and damage rolls to afflict many different targets. In the middle of combat, rolling that much breaks the tension. \par
If you\rquote d rather roll damage the old way, it\rquote s 1D6 damage for every 3% of Lethality. So a weapon with 35% would do 12D6 HP damage.\cell\row\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\par
With explosive weapons, Kill Radius attacks don\rquote t need to be as precise as ordinary attacks; hitting a zone within the Kill Radius of a target is enough. That adds +20% to the chance to hit.\par
A failed attack roll means the Kill Radius lands harmlessly outside the intended area. The attack does no harm\emdash but may still suppress targets (see \b SUPPRESSION\b0 , below). Whether a failed Kill Radius attack does unwanted collateral damage is up to the Game Moderator.\par
\b MANY TARGETS:\b0  A single attack with a Kill Radius usually affects everyone in the Kill Radius. If that doesn\rquote t make sense for the situation, the Game Moderator can decide who gets hit.\par
The Game Moderator is welcome to let players roll the Lethality results for NPCs to speed things up. But really, you need to roll Lethality only for characters who are important enough to track in detail. Since even a failed Lethality roll inflicts between 2 and 20 damage, it\rquote s safe to just assume that most humans caught in a Kill Radius are either dead or incapacitated.\par
\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.7\tab Explosions\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 If your Protagonist wants to disable or destroy a structure or vehicle, an explosive or other form of Lethal attack might be their best bet. Such large objects have their own Hit Points (see \b VEHICLES,\b0  page \lang3081 68\lang1033 ), and they are considered huge targets (see \b HUGE\b0 , page \lang3081 58\lang1033 ).\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang3081 For example, if your Protagonist wanted to gain entry into the abbey's sanctum, he or she might try setting a ceramic grenade beside its door. The GM might rule that the thick door has 12HP and an Armor rating of 5. Assuming the grenade is lobbed (Athletics test) such that the door is within its kill radius (5 yards), when it goes off the door will take damage. Because the object is treated like a HUGE target, the normal Lethality 10% damage is translated into an automatic 10 HP damage reduced by Armor down to 5 HP. So, while the explosion makes a lot of noise, the door is less than half broken down. Time to get another grenade or two.\lang1033\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.8\tab Fear in Combat\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Being involved in combat is inherently frightening for most people. However, certain types of attacks which devastate an entire area are especially terror-inducing. When faced with such destruction \endash  whether from a mundane weapon (e.g., \lang3081 a barrage from a bank of ballistae\lang1033 ) or something supernatural \endash  primal instinct kicks in to prevent a person from placing themselves in mortal peril.\par
The GM can nominate that any massively damaging attack is \b Terror-Inducing.\b0  Any character who knowingly seeks to enter a region targeted by such an attack will hesitate and go to ground \endash  \i even if the attack does not succeed\i0 . The only way to stifle this primal terror is by voluntarily sacrificing 1 SAN.\par
The types of attacks which might be ruled Terror-Inducing include:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Attacks (mundane or supernatural) that inflict Lethal Damage to a Kill Zone,\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Attacks which have previously been witnessed to inflict Unnatural effects worthy of a SAN test,\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Anything else the GM believes would strike extreme fear into combatants.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Note that these effects do not apply to a combatant who is not aware that he or she is straying into an area targeted by the Terror-Inducing attack \endash  when in doubt, call for an \b Alertness\b0  test.\par
\pard A character adapted to violence (see \b ADAPTING TO SAN LOSS\b0  on page \lang3081 77\lang1033 ) loses no SAN for braving a Terror-Inducing attack. For NPCs, it\rquote s easiest to assume the average human goes to ground when faced with such attacks. Only insane, hardened, or fanatical enemies stand up to such intense fear.\par
