\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.9.6\tab Armor Piercing Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An armor piercing weapon reduces the Armor value of a target by a number of points. If the weapon description notes it as armor-piercing it will normally also specify the reduction \endash  if no number is given, assume the attack reduces effective armor by 5.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.10\tab Optional Spot Rules for Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\b0\f1\fs22 There\rquote s a fair amount of variety in weaponry available during this era. Their usefulness in adventures may be limited, of course, depending on who or what the Protagonists face.\par
\pard The primary game statistics relating to different types of weapons may be found on the Example Weapons Table on page 54. The availability of any class of weapon will be dictated by the scarcity of weapon resources in the particular game setting (see preceding section). There are a wide variety of weapon variations throughout the Medieval era depending on culture and purpose. \par
What follows are some spot rules for Protagonists who have access to common Medieval Era weapons.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\lang1033\b\f0 4.10.1\tab Concealing Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\b0\f1 Knives and daggers can be concealed under ordinary clothing. Someone deliberately looking for a concealed weapon can attempt an \b Alertness\b0  test to spot it. A short sword or club means a +20% Alertness bonus.\par
If a Protagonist is wearing a heavy coat or cloak, they can attempt to conceal items like broadswords or axes and incur no Alertness bonus.\par
There\rquote s no way to conceal a large melee weapon.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\lang1033\b\f0 4.10.2\tab Hand-to-Hand Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\b0\f1 Unarmed attacks, like punching, kicking, and strangling, use the \b Unarmed\b0  Combat skill. All melee weapons use the \b Melee Weapons\b0  skill.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\lang1033\b\f0 4.10.3\tab Ranged Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\b0\f1 Ranged weapons that are aimed (e.g., crossbows, bow, and slings) use the \b Ranged Weapons\b0  skill. All require some kind of ammunition (arrows, bolts) and are useless if the supply is exhausted. Primitive weapons that are thrown (e.g., spears) use \b Athletics\b0  skill.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\lang1033\b\f0 4.10.4\tab Fighting on Horseback\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\b0\f1 If a combatant on horseback attacks an enemy who is on foot, the height advantage of the attacker affords an advantage. All such attacks are made at +20%. Similarly, attempts made by mounted combatants to dodge or fight back against attackers on foot receive a bonus of +20%. These bonuses only apply if there is a significant height advantage (and don\rquote t apply when a rider is attacking something much larger than human-sized).\par
Note that whenever fighting from horseback, a combatant\rquote s effective combat skill is the \ul lesser\ulnone  of their \b Ride\b0  skill and their normal relevant combat skill.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.10.5\tab Siege Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Many unnatural things that Protagonists face are inscrutable perversions of physics no more vulnerable to explosions than they are to crucifixes. This never stops Protagonists from trying.\par
The most damaging weapons available in the Medieval Era are the siege weapons that are used to fight land wars and besiege castles and cities. These are all weighty weapons that require an entire team of skilled persons to operate and take considerable time to place and move. Siege Weapons take a long time to load and fire. \par
Most catapults and trebuchets can fire whatever will fit into their basket. Rocks, weapons, incendiary materials, even corpses have all been flung in the general direction of the enemy. \par
During most engagements, siege engines are built on the spot using available timber. The manpower and expense to move them from battlefield to battlefield isn\rquote t cost effective.\par
\pard As shown in the Table of Example Weapons (page 54), the rate of fire for ordnance is low; preparing even a small weapon takes 5 or more combat turns; larger ones can take 10 turns or more to re-load.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Aiming and Firing Siege Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 The team of people preparing a siege weapon for firing must all work together to position it appropriately and calibrate it to fire in the desired direction. Every person involved must possess some rating in the \b Siege Weapons\b0  skill to usefully contribute to the process. Once the piece is ready, whoever was directing the placement makes a skill test against his or her \b Siege Weapons\b0 . A success means the projectile lands in the desired location; failure means that the weapon fired but the projectile lands somewhere other than the chosen target (the GM should choose where it went or use dice to pick a spot 2D10 yards in random direction from the actual target). A fumble means that the siege weapon misfired in some way \endash  perhaps a piece of the weapon breaks or the load falls far short, striking allies. A critical success does not increase the lethality of the shot but will improve the morale of the crew firing the weapon.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Range of Siege Weapons\par
\pard\cf0\i0\f1 The range of a siege weapon is affected both by its type and load. Game Masters can extrapolate range for heavier loads. This range assumes the load is a solid projectile, such as a single large rock. A m\'e9lange of smaller materials will have half the range for an equivalent weight. But the load will scatter in mid-air causing damage over a wider area \endash  triple the kill zone from the table on page 54.\par
