\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10461\pard\intbl\sa200\sl276\slmult1 If a Protagonist is beaten, whipped, or subject to another type of physical torture, he or she is required to make a \b CON\'d73\b0  test. The damage accrued from the experience depends on the level of success or failure of this roll:\par
\pard\intbl\fi-360\li720\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Critical Success:\b0  1D10 HP damage for the whole session, no matter how brutal.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Success by 20 or more:\b0  1D3 damage for every 50 strikes (or equivalent).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Regular Success:\b0  Lethality 3% for every 50 strikes (i.e., 3% for 50 strikes, 6% for 100 strikes, and so on).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Failure:\b0  Lethality 2% for every 20 strikes.\par
\pard\intbl\fi-357\li714\sa200\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Fumble:\b0  1D20+5 HP damage for the torture with\i  \i0 any torture over 50 strikes results in immediate death.\par
\pard\intbl\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Torture also takes a toll on the torturer\rquote s and victim\rquote s mental health. The torturer must make violence-related SAN tests until they\rquote ve become inured to torturing others. \par
In some cases, torture is a form of corporal punishment, meant to do nothing other than confer pain on the victim. Other times, torture is a means to extract information. While the victim may want to stay silent, the pain of torture (or even the promise of torture) can convince the victim to divulge what they know.\par
When the victim wants to resist blabbering everything they know, they must attempt a \b Willpower Points \'d7 3\b0  test. On a success, the victim can say, or not say, whatever they want. For every turn of torture that the victim survives, they lose 1D4 WP in addition to any HP lost. The \b WP\'d73\b0  test must be attempted after any turn of torture.\par
If the WP roll is a fumble, the victim can\rquote t help but tell the entire truth. A regular failure means that the victim must reveal one fact or detail, but they can choose what that is. A torturer who succeeds on an \b Insight\b0  test can tell when the truth is being told, and can choose to continue the torture even after the victim talks.\cell\row\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.11.2\tab Falling\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Falling is extremely dangerous to humans. Even a bad slip can be lethal. A fall from a short distance (one to three yards) does 1D6 damage, or 2D6 if it\rquote s a particularly uncontrolled fall. Beyond that, a fall instead has a Lethality rating of 1% per yard fallen. A Protagonist who survives a fall must make a \b CON\'d75\b0  test or be \b STUNNED\b0  (see page \lang3081 52\lang1033 ).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.11.3\tab Suffocation\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Suffocation is a slow death. If your Protagonist takes a deep breath before holding it, he or she can go without breathing for CON\'d75 turns. After that, your Protagonist\rquote s oxygen-starved brain begins to die. Once every turn, make a \b CON\'d75\b0  test. If it fails, your Protagonist suffers 1D6 HP damage. If the CON test succeeds, your Protagonist suffers 1 HP damage instead. This continues until your Protagonist can breathe again or he or she dies.\par
If your Protagonist doesn\rquote t get a breath before suffocating, the damage starts immediately and lasts until someone clears his or her airway with a \b First Aid\b0  test. Armor does not protect against suffocation damage.\par
