Taking a powerful sedative (e.g., drinking heavily, \i requies magna\i0 ) gives your Protagonist a +20% bonus to resist an acute episode of a disorder at the cost of a \u8722?20% penalty to everything else. Using such drugs frequently makes addiction to them a likely result of your Protagonist\rquote s next disorder. If that happens, the drugs no longer confer any bonus to reduce acute episodes of a disorder, but still inflict the penalty.\cell\row\pard\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.7.2\tab Sample Disorders \par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 There are many adaptations the mind makes when exposed to traumatic events, whether they be violence and gore, feelings of utter helplessness, or the inherent \lquote wrongness\rquote  of unnatural Cthulhu Mythos beings. The specific disorder received by a Protagonist should never be a random roll on a table, but something specifically selected to relate to the trauma they suffered.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Alcohol Habituation\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 Your Protagonist relies on intoxicating liquor to get by. However much harm the addiction causes, your Protagonist needs the relief it offers. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, an overwhelming need. Feeding it usually imparts a \u8722?20% penalty to stats and skills for a few hours due to intoxication or distraction. And even in the best of times, going 24 hours without feeding the addiction costs 1D6 WP and prevents your Protagonist from recovering any WP. Every further 24 hours costs 1D6 WP. At 2 or fewer WP, your Protagonist does irrational, self-destructive things to feed the addiction.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Amnesia\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 This is a common disorder from encounters with the unnatural. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, which erases all memory of the episode until your Protagonist finds a way to bring it back.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Hearing Voices\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 From time to time your Protagonist experiences auditory hallucinations in which you hear voices which others cannot. Often these are running commentaries about your thoughts or actions, usually critical and derogatory. Any time you lose 2+ SAN in any single roll, the voices return for 6+1D6 hours. You can try to hide it from those around you, but while in the grip of one of episodes you are very distracted and will automatically fail any Alertness or Search rolls and suffer a \endash 20% penalty to any other action requiring concentration.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Mania\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 Your Protagonist displays a euphoric and perhaps irritable mood that is consistently present. This may include frenzied activity for no obvious reason, uncharacteristic garrulousness, a random stream\u8208?of\u8208?consciousness flow of ideas, or difficulty sleeping. An acute episode is triggered whenever your Protagonist loses 2+ SAN in a single roll. During an acute episode all tasks which require concentration or fine control are at \b one\u8208?fifth chance.\b0\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Melancholia\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 Acute melancholia means total despair and a crushing inability to get anything done. It sometimes takes the shape of overwhelming guilt. An acute episode is triggered by reminders of past traumas your Protagonist suffered or inflicted, which can come in the most surprising forms and moments. During an acute episode, every skill or stat test costs 1D4 WP.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Obsession\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 Your Protagonist becomes fixated on some person, place, event, act, or idea. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, which lasts days. In that time, any long-term action or skill use\emdash anything taking more than a few hours\emdash is at \u8722?20% because your Protagonist\rquote s mind is so often wrapped around its obsession.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Paranoid Delusions\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 A delusional state of extreme suspicion, in which a fear of invisible enemies pervades one\rquote s world-view. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode. Unless your Protagonist finds a way to stifle his or her delusions, he or she can\rquote t trust or rely on anyone. Every event, every disagreement or source of suspicion is a clue to a conspiracy against the Protagonist.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Phobia or Philia\par
\pard\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 A common affliction arising from traumatic experiences is the development of an irrational fear of something related (directly or by association) with the incident. The term \i\ldblquote phobia\rdblquote\i0  was coined in about 1800 as a term to describe such debilitating conditions (prior to that, the disorder would be less-scientifically termed \i\ldblquote fear of \'85\rdblquote\i0 ). Whenever a Protagonist is in the presence of a trigger for his or her phobia, he or she must make a \b SAN\b0  test (even if the trigger is not terrifying in any way to others). Failure means an acute episode has been triggered, during which there\rquote s little choice but to suffer the Flee or Submit response to temporary insanity (see page 72). A nearby box provides some examples of phobias; searching online will reveal a huge array of other (sometimes quite weird) phobias.\par
A less common response to experiencing something shocking is the development of an irrational fetish or allure for something odd that is associated with the situation (perhaps which somehow related to the Protagonist\rquote s survival). These are called philias and work in a similar way to phobias in that whenever the afflicted Protagonist is in the presence of his or her irrational fetish a \b SAN\b0  roll is required to maintain any degree of self\u8208?control. If failed, an acute episode results during which the Game Moderator will dictate your Protagonist\rquote s actions until he or she regains control.  The list of phobias shown nearby can be converted into philias by simply inverting them: for example, where scotophobia is a fear of darkness, scotophilia is an obsessive and irrational predisposition to shroud oneself in darkness.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Plagued By Nightmares\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 Your Protagonist feels exhausted all the time, barely able to get out of bed in the morning. It might be that some terribly traumatic encounter has left its scars upon them, or it may be just the accumulated stresses of a lifestyle with too much mental fatigue. But being bereft of energy does not equate to being well rested \endash  in fact, your Protagonist sleeps poorly and is always waking to anxiety-inducing memories from the past. An acute episode is triggered by tangible reminders of past traumas your Protagonist suffered or inflicted. In an acute episode, the Game Moderator chooses one effect: your Protagonist either reacts violently to threats only the Protagonist perceives, or suffers an acute bout of melancholy. (See \b MELANCHOLIA\b0  nearby for details.)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\fi-864\li864\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\i\f0 Self-Love (Narcissism)\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\lang3081\i0\f1 There are some whose certainty in their own pre-eminence knows no bound. Francis Bacon described such individuals as being \i sui amantes sine rivali \i0 (\ldblquote lovers of themselves without rival\rdblquote ) \endash  today we would call them narcissists. Some people afflicted with this disorder see themselves as messiahs, or as exempt from ordinary morality. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, in which every hint of doubt about your Protagonist\rquote s superiority fills him or her with indignation. That causes every use of a stat or skill to get help or make a good impression to fail.\par
