If this roll fails, the researcher becomes convinced that the account is gibberish. No matter how many days or weeks he or she invests in studying it, that belief will prevent any deeper understanding of its contents.\par
If this roll is a \i critical success\i0 , the researcher becomes obsessed with the account \endash  and will want to pursue its analysis at all costs. This might present some difficult situations, but also means the research (see below) will be completed in \b half\b0  the normal time.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.1.4\tab Investing Time\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Delving into a weighty account of the Mythos might take months, especially if it is rendered in rambling and confusing language; on the other hand, the information might be presented in a form that only takes a few minutes to comprehend. You as Game Moderator should make a call as to the amount of time that a Protagonist must invest in order to properly appreciate the contents of the knowledge source \endash  in general, the more cryptic and voluminous, the longer it will take. Conceivably, some records featuring elliptical logic might take months to properly understand.\par
If the Game Moderator determines that some form of skill test is required to comprehend the information (e.g., if it is in a foreign language or recorded in a highly unorthodox way), that roll should only be allowed \i after\i0  the necessary research time has been invested. In general, it isn\rquote t necessary for the research process to be uninterrupted, but a long break might prove a setback which lengthens the overall task.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.1.5\tab Dangers of Understanding\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Lovecraft famously wrote that the most merciful thing in the world is mankind\rquote s inability to correlate all the pieces of knowledge at its disposal. It\rquote s this \ldblquote island of ignorance\rdblquote  that saves humanity from going insane from the realization of the true horrors underlying the world. Deliberately diving into the study of the hidden truth is a potentially perilous undertaking.\par
Revelations about terrible or shocking events or disgusting practices of Cthulhu Mythos entities or their followers, might warrant a \b SAN\b0  Loss.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.1.6\tab Skill Increases\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 The main reason to unlock the hidden wisdom of Mythos accounts or other obscure knowledge-sources is to gain information that is relevant to the state of the current world or the scenario/campaign that is being played. In this regard, you as Game Moderator should reward successful research with some helpful details or facts which will aid in solving a problem or remaining alive in the broken world.\par
In addition to this, you might rule that the knowledge learned through research increases the Protagonist\rquote s skill ratings in some way. The most common \lquote reward\rquote  is an improvement to the \b Unnatural\b0  skill (which captures hidden knowledge about the Cthulhu Mythos and its attendant horrors). \par
A minor account might provide +5 skill points (or fewer) to Unnatural, while certain rare and shocking accounts might offer as much as +15. \par
When improving the Unnatural skill, don\rquote t forget that a Protagonist\rquote s Sanity cannot ever be higher than (99 minus the Unnatural skill rating). If changing this cap means current Sanity is too high, that number must also be reduced to match the new Maximum SAN.\par
In addition to learning about the Unnatural, successful research might improve other knowledge-based skills as well. For example:\par
\pard\fi-720\li1080\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang3081\bullet\tab Information about obscure human beliefs might improve an \b Occult\b0  specialization\par
\bullet\tab Information about events or places from the distant past might improve \b History\b0\par
\bullet\tab Information about folklore specific to a geography might improve a \b Foreign Court/Kingdom\b0  specialization and/or the \b Folklore\b0  skill\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 More mundane knowledge might be learned as well, which improves Art, Craft, First Aid, Homeland, Quadrivium, Religion, Trivium, etc.\lang1033\par
Usually the amount of skill gained through such means will be variable and relatively small (e.g., 1D4 to 1D10).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.1.7\tab Learning Rituals\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Mythos accounts may also include descriptions of rituals which, if correctly performed, can create a supernatural effect. Rituals typically involve (potentially complex) patterns of action, chants, and associated paraphernalia. The manifestations created through rituals can be significant, but unlike magic in most tabletop roleplaying games such supernatural workings are laborious. They are typically time-consuming and may require the coordinated actions of a group of people to have any chance of succeeding. \par
Despite such inherent limitations, supernatural rituals represent perhaps the most powerful source of otherworldly influence which Protagonists (or their human adversaries) are ever likely to have under their control. As such there are some individuals who scour the world searching for tomes which can instruct them in such rituals. \par
When a Protagonist has successfully read a tome in its entirety you as Game Moderator should provide him or her with a list of any rituals it contains. Not every account contains rituals, and not every description of supernatural effects in an account is detailed enough to allow it to be reproduced. But for those that are present in such form, you should provide a sketchy description of what the ritual seems designed to do. This should be a description in vague game-world terms rather than in terms of game mechanics: \ldblquote seems designed to bring forth a shadow entity\rdblquote  is preferable to \ldblquote summons a Night-Gaunt\rdblquote .\par
A Protagonist might decide to attempt to study the specifics of a ritual described in a tome. If so, he or she will need to devote time and effort to that endeavor. This is \i in addition to\i0  the time spent researching the account itself and represents study that can only begin when its information has been consumed in full.\par
Exactly how much time is needed to study a given ritual depends on its complexity \endash  that is, whether it is considered \b Simple\b0 , \b Complex\b0 , or \b Elaborate. \b0 Typically, the more powerful the potential effects of a ritual, the more complex it will be.\par
\b Simple\b0  rituals take research of the order of \i hours or days\i0  to learn; \b Complex\b0  rituals can only be learned through the application of \i days or weeks\i0  of study; and \b Elaborate\b0  rituals can take \i weeks, months, or years\i0  to master. The time investment to learn a ritual does not have to be a single continuous block of research but can be split across many shorter periods of intense study.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Rolling to Learn A Ritual\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 If the Protagonist invests the requisite time, he or she will still need to make a roll at the end of the period to see whether the time invested paid off. The Protagonist must attempt a \b SAN\b0  roll \endash  and \i fail\i0  the roll \endash  to learn the ritual. \par
If the roll \b does not\b0  indicate a successful learning of the ritual, it means the Protagonist does not grasp the nuances required to master it. He or she can try again but will need to start from the beginning and again invest the same amount of time again before re-attempting the test. \par
If, on the other hand, the roll \b does\b0  indicate the Protagonist learned the ritual, he or she loses SAN. This is the price of internalizing unnatural truths about the universe and weird techniques for manipulating it. For \b Simple\b0  rituals, the Sanity loss should be modest (e.g., 1 point, 1D4, or 1D6); for \b Complex\b0  rituals a more substantial loss is warranted (e.g., 1D6, 1D8, or 1D10), while learning \b Elaborate\b0  rituals will always be damaging to Sanity (e.g., 1D10, 1D12, or 1D20 point loss). Learning an Elaborate ritual \i also\i0  grants a Protagonist +1 percentile in the \b Unnatural\b0  skill.\par
Once a ritual has been successfully learned, the Protagonist may attempt to perform it (see below).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Mythos Accounts With Multiple Rituals\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Some written accounts, in particular so-called \lquote grimoires\rquote , contain descriptions of many different supernatural rituals. Learning rituals from such sources requires each effort to be attempted separately, using the method described above.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Keeping Failed Rolls Secret\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 The Game Moderator may choose to keep the SAN roll made at the conclusion of a research attempt secret from the player. If the outcome is a clear success or failure the Protagonist should recognize it as such, but if the roll was a marginal success or failure the Game Moderator might choose to tell the player that the Protagonist \i believes\i0  he or she has memorized all the subtleties but is not 100% sure. The only way to know for certain is to attempt the ritual \endash  and if the learning attempt was a failure, such an attempt will never properly succeed. Although it may still generate an unintended supernatural effect.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 9.2\tab Performing Rituals\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The specific actions, chants, and paraphernalia required to successfully perform a ritual are particular to each and should be designed as part of the ritual\rquote s description.\par
Any attempt to carry out a ritual without the necessary knowledge or components is doomed to failure \'85 although it is possible that flawed ritual activities might still generate some kind of supernatural effect, just not the one intended by the person conducting the ritual. The Game Moderator should use his or her judgement to determine any such random supernatural side-effects; they should almost always be dangerous and detrimental to those involved.\par
In terms of game mechanics, the successful performance of a ritual (once the correct pieces are in place) is achieved via an investment of time/effort, the sacrifice of points in one or more game attribute (usually Willpower Points), and a successful Ritual Activation Test (see below). If all these steps are successfully achieved, the supernatural effects of the ritual will manifest.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.2.1\tab Time Invested in the Ritual\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 The amount of time required to perform a ritual depends on its complexity rating \endash  \b Simple\b0 , \b Complex\b0 , or \b Elaborate\b0 .\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Simple\b0  rituals are relatively quick to carry out, requiring somewhere between a turn and a minute.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Complex\b0  rituals are more time-consuming, needing somewhere between a few minutes and an hour.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Elaborate\b0  rituals are serious undertakings, consuming anything from a few hours to a day or maybe more.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 During the time taken to perform a ritual, assume that all participants are completely occupied (chanting, carrying out prescribed actions, using paraphernalia in particular ways). A short interruption might not destroy the momentum of the ritual but a longer break likely will.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.2.2\tab Powering the Ritual\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 The description of a ritual should outline the type and number of personal attribute points that must be sacrificed to provide mental energies that fuel the supernatural effect.\par
The most common form of sacrifice is Willpower Points \endash  to create relatively minor effects might only require 5 or 6 WPs; a substantial effect might require 15; a vastly powerful effect might require 30; and a truly cosmic-level effect might need 100 or more WPs. \par
\pard When a Protagonist makes a deliberate sacrifice of WPs, check to see whether the new total carries any effect upon him or her (see \b WILLPOWER POINTS\b0 , page \lang3081 46\lang1033 ). In particular, remember that reaching a WP total of 1 or 2 indicates a mental collapse of some kind, and reaching 0 WP causes unconsciousness.\par
Whenever a sacrifice of WP is called for, a participant in the ritual may always choose to sacrifice points of permanent POW instead \endash  each such point is equivalent to 10 WPs for the purposes of fueling a ritual. Such sacrificed points do not refresh, but Protagonists can attempt \b DOWNTIME\b0  activities to try to get some back (see page \lang3081 80\lang1033 ) \par
Some rituals also call for a sacrifice of Hit Points, either from the participants or from elsewhere (animal, human, or other living entity). Note that Protagonists who knowingly harm another person, or even cruelly harm or kill an animal are likely to be subject to Sanity loss due to \b VIOLENCE\b0  (see page \lang3081 70\lang1033 ).\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Depending on the nature of the specific ritual, it may be possible for several people to cooperate in the performance. For especially large effects this may be the only way to generate enough mental energies. While the leader of the ritual must have learned it in full (using the process described in the previous section), helpers can be instructed through simple notes and rote learning. Each assistant chooses for themselves how many points of attributes they will sacrifice. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.2.3\tab The Ritual Activation Test\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 If the requisite amount of time has been devoted to the ritual and the necessary number of attribute points sacrificed, the individual leading the performance may make a roll to see if the effort was ultimately successful.\par
Successfully activating a ritual depends on the ritual leader\rquote s Sanity, but success is more likely the \i lower\i0  that number. The \b Ritual Activation Test\b0  is a SAN test that must be \i failed\i0  for the ritual to work as planned. \par
If the roll indicates the ritual did \i not\i0  work, all the chanting and ceremony has been for naught. The ritual leader has two options \endash  he or she can either:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Abandon the ritual:\b0  nothing supernatural happens at all, and half of the sacrificed points are returned to all participants; or\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Force a connection\b0  to the supernatural: this involves the leader personally sacrificing 1 POW permanently to turn a failed roll to a successful one. The ritual effects happen after all, despite the roll. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 9.2.4\tab Sanity Costs to Ritual Participants\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 The simple act of being involved in a supernatural ritual performance is damaging to a character\rquote s Sanity, regardless of whether the ritual was successful or not.\par
If the performance was completed but something went awry (e.g., insufficient mental energy was raised, or the Ritual Activation Test indicated the effort was fruitless), all participants suffer an automatic SAN loss. For rituals intended to create small effects this will be modest, perhaps just 1 SAN point; if attempting a substantial supernatural effect, the loss is 1D4; if attempting a vastly powerful effect it might be 1D6; and for a cosmic effect it might be 1D20.\par
On the other hand, if the ritual succeeded and the supernatural effect is generated it is quite likely that the experience of witnessing something bizarre created by one\rquote s own actions will damage each participants Sanity. The precise losses should reflect the effect that is created, as described by the spell description. As a guideline, a minor supernatural effect might warrant a SAN loss of 1 point, a substantial one might be worth 1D8, a vast effect might lead to a loss of 1D12, and a truly cosmic manifestation might cause a Sanity loss of anything up to 1D100. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 9.3\tab Objects with Unnatural Power\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 As Game Moderator, you may wish to include in your game items with the power to create supernatural effects reminiscent of those wrought through rituals. Using such an item does not require any special training or learning, and no Ritual Activation Test is needed. The user of an object with supernatural powers may, however, still need to sacrifice attribute points to fuel the effect (as per the GM\rquote s description of the item) and might suffer SAN loss from the experience.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb240\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 10.0\tab Supernatural Effects\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 There are lots of weird, supernatural things that can happen in your game of \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 . In most cases, the style of weirdness and its scope of effect should be tied to the specific setting, or the current adventure/campaign/plotline being played out. As such \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  doesn\rquote t provide a ready-made catalogue of supernatural rituals and effects to plunder. Effects should relate to significant plot points or elements of the setting rather than being generic RPG \lquote spells\rquote .\par
The following guidelines may be helpful to Game Moderators inventing custom supernatural powers for their own game.\par
\trowd\trgaph108\trleft5\trbrdrl\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrt\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrr\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw10 \trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10797\pard\intbl\keep\keepn\s3\sb120\sa120\cf2\b\f0 Designing Supernatural Effects: General Principles\par
\pard\intbl\cf0\b0\f1 Supernatural effects in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  are unlike the forms of magic that appear in most roleplaying games, especially games set in the fantasy genre. Rather than wielding a flashy fireball into the midst of combat, a ritual magician in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  might create a supernatural effect as the result of hours of ritual incantation placing his or her mind into communion with extradimensional horrors.\par
The following general guidelines will help you in depicting magic in a suitably low\u8208?key and creepy fashion:\par
\pard\intbl\fi-360\li720\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Supernatural Effects are seldom flashy:\b0  while some spells might create a spectacular if shocking manifestation of unnatural horror, most work with little or no visible or physical effect. Frequently, people who aim to unleash supernatural effects have no way to tell whether their ritual succeeded or not, until hours, days, or even weeks have passed. And even then, its effects may be subtle changes that most people would never notice.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Supernatural Effects are usually time\u8208?consuming to create:\b0  many supernatural effects require lengthy rituals which are repetitious and wearying to perform. While there are a handful of smaller, casual effects which might be useful in a tactical, fast\u8208?paced situation, most play out far too slowly to help in tactical environments.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Supernatural Effects are \i ALWAYS\i0  dangerous to invoke:\b0  generating a supernatural effect is equivalent to opening one\rquote s mind and essence to the unknowable forces which make up the Cthulhu Mythos. These powers are inherently corrosive to reality as we know it. So, coming into direct mental or physical connection with them always causes some form of lasting damage to the spellcaster, and maybe others as well.\par
\pard\intbl\fi-357\li714\sa120\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Supernatural Effects are the enemy of Sanity:\b0  Connecting with the forces of the Mythos is inherently dangerous to one\rquote s Sanity. In game terms this manifests as a mandatory sacrifice of SAN; but in narrative terms you should play up the highly disturbing experience of touching an unknown and unknowable extra\u8208?dimensional force whose very existence is anathema to everything that the caster has ever known or experienced. Generating supernatural effects should hurt. Every single time.\cell\row\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\par
