\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\caps0\f1\fs22 While the rules presented in this System Reference Document provide a fully-playable (if generic) tabletop roleplaying game, they are designed to also serve as the rules foundation for future games. Several resources are collected here which may assist with the design and definition of such games.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb480\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 11.0\tab Designing New Archetypes\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Section 2.5 describes a representative selection of Protagonist Archetypes suitable for games set in the \lang3081 Medieval Era\lang1033 . While these are varied enough to support a wide range of character types, situations will inevitably arise where none of the pre-defined Archetypes meets the needs of describing a class of Protagonists or NPCs important to the setting.\par
When this happens, the best solution is to simply create a new Archetype \endash  which is fortunately not difficult.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 11.1\tab Archetype Building in a Nutshell\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The notes below give a set of helpful guidelines that can assist in making the design choices that define a brand-new Archetype. However, at its simplest, the mechanical process of defining an Archetype is very simple. Each Archetype needs:\par
