\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 11.2\tab Step 1 \endash  Defining the Archetype Concept\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Before diving into the specifics of building game-mechanics for your new Archetype concept, it is worth spending some time making sure the idea is built around a clear concept. How is this Archetype going to be different from others already defined for the setting? In what ways is it filling a gap that none of the existing Archetypes can cover? Is the idea too specific to one situation \endash  and could be broadened out to cover a related category of character types? Or is it too abstract, and in need of refinement to bring it back to something that others will intuitively recognize as an appropriate category of characters for this setting? Having a good concept in mind will make everything that follows much easier, so don\rquote t rush your thinking about the core concept.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 11.3\tab Step 2 \endash  Picking Recommended Statistics\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Each Archetype usually has one or two recommended Statistics that should (ideally) be higher-than-average for characters of that Archetype. Picking these is usually a matter of simple extrapolation from your core concept. Is the Archetype largely driven by knowledge? Then maybe INT should be in the list somewhere. Are individuals of the Archetype defined by their abilities to socialize or establish rapport with other people? Then CHA should definitely be in the list somewhere. If the character type is all about exercising sheer brawn, maybe STR is appropriate \'85 or alternatively if they\rquote re all about fine manipulation or skulking in the shadows, perhaps DEX is a suitable choice. There aren\rquote t too many character types which revolve around healthiness and fortitude, but if yours does maybe you could consider adding CON to the list. It\rquote s fine for your archetype to have just a single recommended statistic, or a couple. More than two is unlikely.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 11.4\tab Step 3 \endash  Starting Bonds and Starting Resources\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Each Archetype needs a starting number of Bonds and a starting Resources rating. Of the budget of 800 points, each Bond slot costs 50 and each rating level in Resources costs 50. A starting point for designing an Archetype is to consider a value of 3 starting bonds and 3 starting resources \endash  this reflects an \ldblquote average\rdblquote  situation for characters; tweak this as seems appropriate.\par
If your concept for the new Archetype is something that has a wide network of contacts, the initial number of Bonds could be 4 or even 5. Each additional bond will, however, reduce the budget of points available for elevating skills so having an extensive network comes with a cost. Some Archetypes are inherently loners: for them, having a smaller number of starting Bonds (perhaps only 2) captures that insular nature and leaves some additional points for resources or skills, depending on your concept for the Archetype. Creating an Archetype with fewer than 2 starting Bonds risks forcing characters into being cut-off from the world around them, and is not usually realistic.\par
For a few rare cases, an Archetype might inherently have one bond that is higher than the normal starting value. If your basic concept inherently places the individual in a leadership role (e.g., your Archetype is supposed to be a local religious leader), it\rquote s ok to add a note that says one of the starting bonds will have a rating value of at least 10. This is usually only meaningful for community bonds.\par
Each Archetype also needs a starting Resources value. Think about how many assets the poorest member of the character type might have access to. If they might be a pauper (at least in terms of access to items), maybe consider a low starting Resources score (perhaps a 2, or in extreme cases a 1). On the other hand, if members of the Archetype would typically have ready access to lots of equipment or assets, a value of 4 or 5 might be worth considering. Don\rquote t forget that during the character generation process, it will be possible to sacrifice skill picks to elevate these base ratings, so leaving a rating at a low level doesn\rquote t necessarily mean that every character created using the new Archetype will have a below-average set of items to draw on: it\rquote s only those who choose not to further sacrifice skill picks that will have a small pool of items to draw on. Making the starting Resources value too high will significantly restrict the number of skills that the Archetype will have at an elevated level. (So, while it would be possible to set your Archetype\rquote s starting Resources at an impressive score of 12, that would use up 600 of the 800 points in the budget, leaving nothing much for skill enhancement; so characters of that Archetype would all universally \ldblquote wealthier-than-most\rdblquote  but lacking in any specific skill. This isn\rquote t usually an interesting choice.)\par
Once you\rquote ve decided on the appropriate number of starting Bonds and starting Resources rating, multiply both numbers by 50 and subtract them from the starting budget of 800. Whatever is left is available for spending on skills.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 11.5\tab Step 4 \endash  Skills With Elevated Starting Ratings\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 As described on page \lang3081 31\lang1033 , each skill has a base rating which every character has as a starting value, regardless of their Archetype. For skills that are directly related to the main activities of an Archetype, the beginning rating will be higher to reflect specialized training and/or experience gained through undertaking tasks particular to the Archetype. These elevated starting scores are purchased on a 1-for-1 basis, trading 1 point from the Archetype build budget for a +1 bump in one skill, above its base value. So, if the normal base value for \b Search\b0  is 20 and your concept for the Archetype suggests its members should have a Search value beginning at 50, you would spend 30 points (50 minus 20) from the budget to achieve that goal.\par
It is traditional to spend points in blocks of 10 (i.e., 10, 20, 30, etc.) to ensure that the Archetype\rquote s starting skill ratings remain a neat multiple of 10, although ignoring that convention won\rquote t break anything from a game mechanics perspective.\par
When deciding on which skills to elevate for your Archetype, it is best to think about the common types of tasks that members of the Archetype would perform often \ul\i in their professional duties\ulnone\i0 , or things would generally be assumed to be good at. \par
It not unusual for an Archetype\rquote s core concept to strongly suggest a half-dozen or so skills which every member of the archetype would excel at, and a larger list of skills which some \endash  but not necessarily all \endash  members would have as a specialty. It is easy to manage this situation by developing two lists:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 A list of core skills, universally relevant to every member of the Archetype \endash  usually this won\rquote t be more than about six skills; and\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 A list of skills which seem like good contenders to be optional specializations for the Archetype.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 First you can spend most (but not all) of the available points from the budget to increase the starting rating of \i every\i0  skill on the core skill list, remembering:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The points cost is the amount you raise the starting value ABOVE the normal base.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 There\rquote s usually diminishing value in increasing a skill\rquote s starting value above 70 or 80 since success is likely and the points might be better spent on elevating another lower-valued skill instead.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 It\rquote s not usually beneficial to elevate a core skill by a tiny amount \endash  anything less than a 30-point nudge for a core skill will feel like you\rquote re short-changing an important part of the Archetype concept.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 No skill under any circumstance can ever be higher than 99%.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Once you\rquote ve got most of the points spent on upgrading the core list, divide whatever\rquote s left into blocks of 30 or 40 points and specify that the Archetype\rquote s skills also include a certain number of picks from your list of optional specializations, with each pick giving that same block-size of elevation to the chosen skill. So, for example, if you were left with 80 points in the budget after core skills had been elevated, you could decide that the Archetype also includes a choice of two skills from your list of possible specializations with each choice elevating the selected skill to a starting value of base plus 40. Alternatively, if there were 90 points left instead you might decide to offer three picks with each offering a 30-point boost over base.\par
If using this structure to provide a level of customization for the Archetype, you should ensure that there\rquote s a good selection of skills to choose from \endash  ideally there should about \i twice\i0  as many options in the list as there are skill picks on offer, to allow plenty of options for diversifying characters. [So, for example, if you\rquote re allowing four picks from the optional specializations list, try to ensure the list has about eight skills to choose from.] \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb480\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 12.0\tab Translating Creatures from D100 Games\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Game Moderators may find statistics for horrific creatures and supernatural effects in the rules or supplements published for other D100 Lovecraftian horror RPGs. The general-purpose guidelines below give some assistance with converting creature-related statistics for use in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 .\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1 In most cases, converting horrific creatures found in other D100 games for use in a \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  game is straightforward. A seven-step process for carrying out such conversions is described below.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 Step 1: Convert Statistics\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 As described on page \lang3081 9\lang1033 , characters and other creatures in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  are principally described in terms of six core capabilities: Strength, Constitution, Dexterity, Intelligence, Power, and Charisma. These are measured on a scale of approximately 3\emdash 18 for a human being. Most D100 games use a similar set of characteristics although the seventh edition of the world\rquote s oldest Lovecraftian roleplaying game chooses to instead measure a character\rquote s core statistics on a 1\emdash 100 scale.\par
If the creature or character being translated has game statistics for anything other than the previously mentioned seventh edition game, the translation is simple:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Strength (sometimes STR) becomes the creature or character\rquote s Strength statistic in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 ; \par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Constitution (CON), Intelligence (INT), Dexterity (DEX), and Power (POW), all become the identically named statistic in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 ; and\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If a creature/character has a listed Appearance (APP) rating, that translates to its Charisma (CHA) in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 . \par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 When translating statistics from the aforementioned seventh edition game, the process is effectively the same, but each number is divided by 5 during the translation (e.g., a CON of 65 for a seventh edition creature would translate to a \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  Constitution statistic of 13).\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1 If the creature or character has a listed Sanity (SAN) score, that same number becomes their SAN score in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 .\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 Step 2: Derive Hit Points and Will Points (and optionally Resources)\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 In \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  two key game attributes, Hit Points and Will Points, are derived from the core statistics. The formulae for deriving these may be found in the section on creating Protagonists, on page \lang3081 11\lang1033 . Once the core statistics have been translated for the Mythos creature or character, these should be calculated exactly as described in the Protagonist generation process.\par
When translating human characters (as opposed to creatures) it may be important for the Game Moderator to be able to gauge how well-resourced the character is. In that situation, scanning through the list of Archetypes (starting on page \lang3081 12\lang1033 ), the Game Moderator can see which most closely relates to the character\rquote s role \endash  the base Resources attribute score for the character can be assumed to be the same as that Archetype. This can be modified up or down by the Game Moderator to reflect a vision for the character\rquote s material \lquote wealth\rquote .\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 Step 3: Deriving Sanity Loss\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 For games which list explicit sanity losses for witnessing Cthulhu Mythos horrors, those same sanity losses can be applied in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 . For games which do not include specific game mechanics for mental stability, use the table on page \lang3081 71\lang1033  to pick an equivalent sanity loss based on how disturbing and/or disgusting a creature is described as being.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 Step 4: Deriving Skills\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 All D100-based games measure skill proficiency of a person or creature on a scale of 0\emdash 100, the same scale used by \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 . So, any skill scores assigned as part of the game statistics for another game can be carried across without the need for any arithmetic. However, each different game uses its own list of skills, each of them a variant way of carving the broad field of human knowledge and abilities into different categorizations. Thus, in converting game statistics from another RPG to \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 , it\rquote s necessary to decide which \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  skill most closely relates to each skill named in the source stat-block.\par
There are four situations that can arise:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b 1.\tab Obvious Match:\b0  The skill named in the source stat-block has an obvious counterpart in the \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  skill list. In this case, simply give the person or creature the corresponding \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  skill with the same percentile rating assigned to the original skill.\par
\b 2.\tab Multiple Match:\b0  The skill named in the source stat-block has similarities with several different \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  skills. In this case, you can either pick one of the \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  skills (ideally the most relevant) and assign all the original skill\rquote s percentile rating to that skill, or you can split up the percentiles among multiple \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  skills.\par
\b 3.\tab Clash:\b0  Sometimes during the translation of many different skill ratings, it will occur that several different foreign-game skills all translate to the same \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  skill. In that case, the person or creature\rquote s percentile rating in that skill should be the \b\i highest\b0\i0  of all the different skills that translate to that skill.\par
\b 4.\tab Novelty Skill:\b0  Some games like to include silly or oddly specific skills (like \ldblquote bake cookies\rdblquote  or \ldblquote defuse nuclear bomb\rdblquote ). You can either ignore these skills altogether or carry them across as similar \lquote additional skills\rquote  (i.e., presume the existence of a cookie baking skill in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 , whose definition you can make up as needed).\par
\pard References to a rating in the \ldblquote Cthulhu Mythos\rdblquote  skill used in other games should all be carried across to \i Cthulhu Eternal\rquote s\i0  \b Unnatural\b0  skill (see page \lang3081 40\lang1033 ).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 Step 5: Deriving Attacks\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Every D100-based game describes the basic attributes of an offensive capability (or attack) in terms of a percentage chance that the attack will hit its target, plus a dice roll to determine the HP damage that the attack inflicts.\par
\pard When converting a stat-block to \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 , each attack mode will typically map to a similar or equivalent weapon skill with the same percentile rating. Damage ratings (die rolls) can either be carried across unchanged, or if the attack mode obviously relates to one of the weapons listed in the examples on page \lang3081 54\lang1033 , you can just use the \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  damage rating for the listed weapon. Where the damage die listed in the source stat-block mention adding a \ldblquote Damage Bonus\rdblquote , consult the material on page \lang3081 52\lang1033  to see whether the \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  attack should also include the equivalent bonus. \par
If converting a stat-block for a creature \endash  especially a large creature, or one with a STR well outside the normal human range \endash  it is probably better to forget about Damage Bonus altogether. Many D100-based games give such massive monstrosities equally massive Damage Bonuses (+3D6 and above): \i Cthulhu Eternal\rquote s\i0  combat system doesn\rquote t seek to model overwhelming damage by means of large pools of dice \endash  instead, it uses the Lethality mechanic. Consider setting the total damage rating of such a creature\rquote s attacks based on its \i overall\i0  damage rating in the source system \endash  that is, the attack\rquote s base damage \i plus\i0  the creature\rquote s stated Damage Bonus. If that total is no-more than 2 dice, then simply set the \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  damage rating for the attack equal to that.   \par
