\pard\keep\keepn\s2\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 Step 6: Deriving Armor value\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Creatures or individuals who have innate protection from damage, or who wear protective equipment may have an Armor value as part of their original statistic block. They may also have a description of the particular type of armor.\par
Armor values from D100-based games can be directly translated across \endash  for example, a Mythos creature with an innate Armor of 2 will have the same Armor rating in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 .\par
\pard An alternate method of assigning an Armor value for worn protection is to consult the table in \b ARMORED\b0  (page \lang3081 57\lang1033 ), locating a roughly-equivalent type of protective equipment and use the Armor value shown in the table.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 Step 7: Defining Special Powers and Defenses\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Perhaps the hardest part of converting stat-blocks for creatures (and sometimes human beings) to \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 , is translating special powers and defenses, including unusual modes of attack. These are sometimes written in a manner that is specific to the game-mechanics for the source system.\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1 There are two basic approaches to converting special powers: \par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 1.\tab finding a similar power already possessed by a creature with \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  stats, or \par
2.\tab converting the individual game mechanics underlying the power into \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  concepts piece-by-piece.\par
\pard For determining appropriate \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  game-statistics to cover special defenses, a good place to start is considering the categories of Defenses described in \b PROTECTION IN COMBAT\b0 , page \lang3081 56\lang1033 . These are: Fragile, Exposed, Armored, Huge, and Transcendent. \par
Furthermore, some creatures have physical forms that are less susceptible to Lethal damage: the box nearby summarizes different levels of protection that the Game Moderator can assign to otherworldly monstrosities.\par
\trowd\trgaph108\trleft5\trbrdrl\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrt\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrr\brdrs\brdrw10 \trbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw10 \trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10797\pard\intbl\keep\keepn\s3\sb120\sa120\cf2\b\f0 Reduced Susceptibility to Lethal Damage\par
\pard\intbl\cf0\b0\f1 The following common forms of protection against Lethal attacks may be assigned to creatures/individuals which are harder to kill than normal humans.\par
\pard\intbl\fi-360\li720\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 RESILIENT:\b0  A successful roll on a Lethal attack does not kill the creature/individual but inflicts Hit Point damage equal to 2D10 minus any Armor rating.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 RESILIENT TO <attack type, e.g., Firearms>:\b0  If attacked with other attack types than the one named, damage/lethality is as per normal. If attacked with Lethal attacks of the nominated type, a successful roll does not kill the creature/individual but inflicts Hit Point damage equal to 2D10 minus any Armor rating.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 PARTIALLY IMMUNE (less than <number, e.g., 20>%): \b0 If the Lethal attack has a Lethality rating less than or equal to the number mentioned, it cannot harm or kill the target \endash  even a successful Lethality roll will cause it zero harm. For Lethal attacks with a Lethality rating \i higher\i0  than the number mentioned, the creature/individual is still not automatically killed on a successful Lethality roll but suffers Hit Point damage equal to 2D10 minus any Armor rating.\par
\pard\intbl\fi-357\li714\sa120\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 IMMUNE:\b0  Is not affected at all any physical attacks, including Lethal attacks.\cell\row\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\par
